He and his wife are co-directors of Wallace Chess Ltd.

Bradford City A.F.C. finished fourth in the Football League Second Division in the 1987-88 season, but lost in the playoffs to Middlesbrough. They also reached the fifth round of the FA Cup, quarter-finals of the League Cup, and semi-finals of the Simod Cup. Captain Stuart McCall and forward John Hendrie left the team at the end of the season.
Bar Hefer, who was born in 1995, won the Miss World Israel 2013 beauty pageant.

Myra H. Strober is an emerita professor of education at Stanford Graduate School of Business in California, USA. She is also on the editorial board of Feminist Economics and was the president of the International Association for Feminist Economics from 1997 to 1999.
Skinner's Nursery in Manitoba created the Ulmus americana 'Skinner Upright' American Elm in 1954.
The English rock band Killing Joke released their first single, "Wardance," in 1980 through Malicious Damage record label, which was also featured on their debut studio album.
TRAPPIST-1b is a planet that orbits an ultracool dwarf star called TRAPPIST-1 in the Aquarius constellation, located about 40 light-years away.
Isaak Mazepa was a Ukrainian politician born in Kostobobriv in 1884 and died in Augsburg in 1952.

The Hereford Cathedral Library in England is a functional theological lending and reference library that also houses significant books and manuscripts related to the history of Herefordshire. It is famous for its chained books, as it is the only library of its kind to have all the chains, rods, and locks still in place.
A Venezuelan politician named José Gregorio Briceño Torrealba was born on July 25, 1965, in Caicara.
Daniel A. Reed was an American actor, playwright, and screenwriter born on July 12, 1892 and died on February 9, 1978.

Francisco Yeste Navarro, a retired Spanish footballer and current manager of CD Eldense, played as an attacking midfielder or left winger. He spent 11 years with Athletic Bilbao, playing in 353 official games and scoring 59 goals.

The Veterans Bridge in St. Cloud, Minnesota is a steel girder bridge that was constructed in 1971 and designed by Howard, Needles, Tammen & Bergendoff. It replaced three previous bridges, including a wooden toll bridge built in 1867, an iron and wood bridge rebuilt in 1887, and a deck truss bridge constructed in 1894.

The Crimple Valley Viaduct, also known as Crimple Viaduct and Crimple Beck Viaduct, is a Grade II* listed railway viaduct in North Yorkshire. It spans 1,875 feet (572 m) with 31 arches, each 52-foot (16 m) in span and reaching a maximum height of 110 feet (34 m) above the Crimple Valley. It was designed by George Hudson for the York and North Midland Railway company and built in 1848 using rusticated grit stone ashlar by contractor James Bray.

Jia Le Channel was a 24-hour TV network on Singtel TV IPTV, featuring Chinese, Hokkien, and Korean programming, including foreign shows for Chinese viewers. It aired on Channel 502 and had Video On Demand on Channel 503 in Singapore.

The song "Proud of the House We Built" was written by Ronnie Dunn, Terry McBride, and Marv Green and recorded by Brooks & Dunn. It was released in June 2007 as the lead single from their album Cowboy Town and reached number 4 on the Billboard Hot Country Songs chart.
In 1999, Playboy magazine celebrated its 45th anniversary by featuring a different Playmate of the Month each month. Here is a list of all the Playmates from that year.

The Saxony-Anhalt Landtag is the state parliament of Saxony-Anhalt in Germany, with 97 members from four political parties. The current ruling coalition is made up of the Social Democratic Party and the Christian Democratic Union, supporting Minister-President Reiner Haseloff's cabinet.

Williams Street Records is an independent record company based in Atlanta, Georgia, founded by Jason DeMarco. It is a joint venture of Williams Street Studios and Warner Music Group, and is distributed through Alternative Distribution Alliance. They have released original music related to their shows on Adult Swim, managed by Chris Hartley and A&R by Jason DeMarco. In 2015, DeMarco announced that the label will only release free music and will no longer sell albums.

Charleston Municipal Airport is a publicly owned airport located in Tallahatchie County, Mississippi, two nautical miles south of the city's central business district. It is classified as a general aviation facility in the National Plan of Integrated Airport Systems for 2011-2015.

The Gillies Range is a mountain range south of Cairns that separates the Far North Queensland coastal plain from the Atherton Tableland. The Gillies Highway, named after William N Gillies, allows road access from Gordonvale to Atherton via the range, known for its 263 corners and 800 m elevation change in 19 km.
The Araberri Basket Club, also called Sáenz Horeca Araberri due to sponsorship, is a basketball team located in Vitoria-Gasteiz, Basque Country, Spain, and competes in LEB Oro.

Acanthogonatus centralis is a spider found in central Argentina and is one of the most common mygalomorphs in the area. Female spiders are similar to A. parana but have a wider fundus of the spermathecae. Male spiders have a smooth bulb and a well-developed tibial apophysis.
Tora Takagi, born on February 12, 1974, is a retired Japanese race car driver.

2002 MS4 is a large Kuiper belt object, discovered in 2002 and considered a likely dwarf planet by Michael Brown. Its estimated diameter ranges from 726 to 934 km, making it one of the 10 largest TNOs and potentially a dwarf planet under IAU guidelines. It is currently 47.2 AU from the Sun and will reach perihelion in 2123. It has been observed 55 times, with precovery images dating back to 1954.

Brill is a Dutch academic publisher established in 1683 in Leiden, Netherlands. It currently publishes over 200 journals and approximately 700 new books and reference works annually, and also offers primary source materials online and on microform for humanities and social sciences researchers. Brill has offices in Leiden and Boston.
During the Twenty-first dynasty of Egypt, Isetemkheb D was the wife of Pinudjem II, who was the High Priest of Amun in Thebes and also her brother.
Glyn Prosser, a Welsh rugby union flanker, played for Neath and was capped four times for Wales. He was part of the team that defeated the touring New Zealanders in 1935.

Jungle World is a left-wing German newspaper founded in 1997 by editors of the Marxist daily Junge Welt. It is now independent and published by Jungle World Verlags GmbH. The newspaper has anti-nationalist and cosmopolitan positions and sells between 12,000 and 16,000 copies. It is known for picking up questions of the Far Left Anti-German spectrum and has been categorized as one of the most important publications of the Anti-German milieu. The newspaper has a pro-Israel position and features political news, analysis, cultural and literary criticism, satire, and a comics page. It also runs a series of blogs on its website.

Jean-Marc Rochette is a French artist who is famous for creating comic book series such as Edmond le Cochon and Le Transperceneige. He is also known for his illustrations of Candide ou l'optimisme by Voltaire and Homer's Odyssey.
The Seyfert galaxy 3C 452 is situated in the Lacerta constellation.

The Popular Socialist Party was a Chilean political party that existed from 1948 to 1957, formed after the Socialist Party of Chile split due to differing views on communism. The anti-communist faction supported a law that divided the party's vote, leading to their expulsion and the adoption of the name Popular Socialist Party. They supported Carlos Ibáñez del Campo's presidential candidacy in 1952 and held positions in his government until 1953. The party later formed the FRAP with other leftist parties and reunited with the Socialist Party of Chile in 1957.

Ted Buckle was an English footballer who played for Manchester United, Everton, and Exeter City in the late 1940s and 1950s. He also briefly played for Dolgellau in the 1961-62 season and was a player-manager at Prestatyn. Buckle joined the Royal Navy at 18 and was spotted by Manchester United while playing for their football team. He scored on his professional debut and later transferred to Everton, where he scored 31 goals in 97 games. Buckle died at the age of 65 in 1990.

Deng Linlin is a Chinese gymnast born on April 21, 1992 in Lixin, Anhui. She won the team gold medal at the 2008 Olympic Games and is a three-time World Cup gold medalist. Deng is also the 2009 World Champion and 2012 Olympic champion on balance beam.

The Borzontul Mare River, also called Borzont River, is a left tributary of the Mureș River in Romania. It flows into the Mureș River near Joseni and is sometimes referred to as the Putna River in its upper reach.

The Yellow Line of the São Paulo Metro runs from Luz to Vila Sônia and is operated by ViaQuatro under a public-private partnership. The line opened in stages, with the first stretch opening in 2010 and two additional stations opening in 2011. The line currently runs from Butantã to Luz and is expected to be fully completed by 2015, with monitoring by Companhia do Metropolitano de São Paulo.

Johan Kristoffer Berntsson, a Swedish figure skater born in Gothenburg on July 13, 1982, has won eight Swedish national championships and five Nordic championships (2000-2010). He was also the first Swede to successfully execute a triple Axel.

Vern Clevenger is a renowned climber and landscape photographer from Oakland, California. He was the first to climb Cholatse in 1982 and resides in Mammoth Lakes with his wife and two children. Clevenger's search for a drug-smuggling airplane in Yosemite National Park in 1977 earned him his first Nikon camera system. He displays his work at the Clevenger Gallery and Studio in Mammoth Lakes, where his family assists him.

Günther Seiffert, a former German racing driver, attempted one World Championship Formula One event in 1962 but failed to qualify. He participated in several non-Championship Formula One races during 1962-63, mostly for Wolfgang Seidel's team, and generally qualified and finished at the back of the grid. Seiffert's best showing was finishing seventh, albeit 12 laps down, at the 1963 Austrian Grand Prix.

Markus Janka, a German ice hockey player born in 1980, is currently not signed to a team. He last played for Schwenninger Wild Wings in the German Ice Hockey League and has also played for Kassel Huskies, Krefeld Pinguine, Straubing Tigers, and ERC Ingolstadt.
Titus Flavius Postumius Titianus was a Roman politician who held the positions of Senator and Consul suffectus during the late 3rd and 4th century AD.

Sarada is a genus of lizards in the Agamidae family, also known as large fan-throated lizards. It consists of three species and is closely related to the Sitana genus, forming the fan-throated lizards group. Sarada is found only in Maharashtra and northern parts of Karnataka in India. The name Sarada comes from a Marathi word for Agamidae.

Shelley Roy, an Australian team handball player born on August 2, 1974, competes for Sydney University HC and the Australian national team. She participated in the 2013 World Women's Handball Championship in Serbia as a representative of Australia.
Hiroki Ishii is a Japanese lightweight kickboxer who won the Super lightweight championship of Rajadamnern Stadium in Muay Thai. He uses Spente Le Stelle as his entrance music.

Mike Hall is a British sports journalist and presenter for ITV's Granada Reports. He started working for the sports department in 2000 and made his on-screen debut six years later. He is also a stand-in presenter for the programme. Hall won the Broadcast Presenter of the Year award in 2014 and is an ambassador for TSC Trust and Randox.

Fata Salkunič, a Slovenian football midfielder, is currently playing for USV Jena in the German Bundesliga. She has also played for ZNK Maribor, Krka Novo Mesto, Hamburger SV, and FC Basel in the past and is a member of the Slovenian national team.

The Women's downhill event at the Albertville 1992 Olympics took place in Meribel. Petra Kronberger from Austria was the previous world champion, Chantal Bournissen from Switzerland was the previous World Cup downhill champion, and Katja Seizinger from Germany was leading the 1992 World Cup.

Leoš Friedl, a retired Czech tennis player, is renowned for his doubles partnership with František Čermák. He has won 16 top-level doubles titles and the 2001 Wimbledon mixed doubles title with Daniela Hantuchová, defeating Mike Bryan and Liezel Huber. Lubomir Gerla was his coach.

Phoenix, son of Agenor and Telephassa, was a brother of Cadmus, Cilix, and Europa. He settled in Asia and named the country Phoenicia after himself. He fathered children with different women, including Carme, Cilix, Phineus, Doryclus, Adonis, and possibly Europa. Telephassa may be the same person as Telephe.

The Derwent Way Bridge, constructed in 1955, was a swing bridge for both road and rail over the Annacis Channel of the Fraser River in British Columbia. It linked Queensborough in New Westminster to Annacis Island in Delta. It was replaced in 1986 by the Annacis Island Swing Bridge.

Yuri Mikhailovich Baturin is a Russian cosmonaut, former politician, and author in constitutional law. He flew on two space missions, Mir EP-4 and ISS EP-1, and was designated a Research Cosmonaut and Flight Engineer, respectively. He graduated from the Moscow Institute of Physics and Technology and was the former head of National Security. He is married to Svetlana Veniaminovna Polubinskaya and has a daughter named Alexandra Yurievna Baturina.

Amy Hill is a Welsh cyclist who currently rides for Team Rytger and previously rode for Abergavenny RC Women's Team. She was part of the British team pursuit squad that won gold and broke the world record at the Juniors world championships in 2013. Hill also competed at the UCI Juniors Track World Championships and represented Wales at the Commonwealth Games in Glasgow in 2014.

Joseph O'Connell Ryan was a Canadian politician, barrister, and editor who was born in Dunnville, Canada West. He was educated at Regiopolis College and married Mary Helena Macmanamin in 1868. Ryan was called to the Ontario bar in 1869 and to the Manitoba bar in 1872. He practiced law in Portage la Prairie and was elected to the Canadian House of Commons as a Member of the Liberal Party in 1874. Ryan served as a judge in the County Court for the Central Judicial District in Manitoba from 1882 to 1916. He died in Los Angeles, California at the age of 96.

The Polish Aviation Museum in Kraków displays old aircraft and engines at the site of the former Kraków-Rakowice-Czyżyny Airport, one of the oldest in the world. The museum opened in 1964 and was ranked eighth best aviation museum by CNN. It initially used four hangars, but a new main building opened in 2010 to improve conditions.
The Sudbury Baronetcy of Eldon in Durham was a title in the English Baronetage created for John Sudbury on 25 June 1685, but became extinct upon his death in 1691.

Super Punch-Out!! is a boxing video game developed and published by Nintendo for the SNES. It was released in North America in 1994 and Europe in 1995. The game features Little Mac as he fights his way to become the World Video Boxing Association champion. Players must knockout their opponent in three minutes to win. The game received praise for its cartoon-like style, colorful opponents, simple gameplay controls, and replay value. However, some reviewers felt that it lacked the overall appeal of its predecessor.

The Thornycroft Baronetcy of Milcomb in Oxfordshire was a title in the English Baronetage, created in 1701 for John Thornycroft, a barrister. The second Baronet died in 1743, causing the title to become extinct.

Quinton de Kock is a South African cricketer who plays for the Titans and the national team. He is a top-order batsman and wicket-keeper who has played regularly in One Day and Twenty20 formats since 2012. He made his Test debut in 2014 and has scored five centuries in his first 20 ODI matches. He has also played for Gauteng and the Highveld Lions in domestic cricket and in the IPL for Sunrisers Hyderabad and Delhi Daredevils.

Vento Aureo is the fifth story arc of JoJo's Bizarre Adventure manga series, written and illustrated by Hirohiko Araki. It was serialized in Weekly Shōnen Jump from 1995 to 1999 and takes place in Italy. The series title is written in Italian as Le Bizzarre Avventure di GioGio. It is referred to as JoJo's Bizarre Adventure Part 5 Giorno Giovanna: Golden Heritage and picks up where the fourth left off, with 155 chapters numbered 440 to 594 and tankōbon volumes numbered 47 to 63. It was preceded by Diamond Is Unbreakable and followed by Stone Ocean.

Doki Doki School Hours is a manga and anime series by Tamami Momose. The manga was published in Bamboo Comics from 1997 and the anime adaptation was created by J.C.Staff, airing on TV Tokyo from April to June 2004. An OVA was also produced and released on the DVDs of the TV series. Both the TV series and OVA were dubbed into English and licensed for release in North America. The series follows homeroom teacher Mika Suzuki and her eccentric students. The anime inherits a lot stylistically from Azumanga Daioh, but the manga predates it by two years and also spawned a series of drama CDs.

James O'Shea, a former footballer from County Kerry, was a successful player on many Kerry underage teams in the 90's, winning an All Ireland Minor title in 1994 and an Under 21 title in 1996. He also played with Cork and his home club St. Michael's/Foilmore, winning County and Munster Intermediate Championships in 2008 and an All Ireland in 2009. He played with Bishopstown and reached a County Championship final in 2004.
Sinnae Station is a railway station on the Gyeongchun Line and will have Seoul Subway Line 6 extended to it by the end of 2015.

Joe Cotton was a Thoroughbred racehorse who won the 1885 Kentucky Derby. He was named after a bookie and was killed in a race in 1888. However, he was bought by Charles Jacobs who reset his shoulder joint and used him as a breeding stallion. By 1895, he was owned by Mr. Newhall and was employed pulling a hack in Medford. He was observed by horseman Frank Ware until a few years before 1905 and is listed as a native stallion in the 1902 edition of the American Stud Book.

Morten Hagen is a Norwegian professional golfer who primarily competes in Scandinavian tours, where he has won multiple events and topped the Nordic League Ranking in 2005. He has also won the Telia Challenge Waxholm in 2005 on the Challenge Tour and made two appearances on the European Tour.

In 2001, Estonia won the Eurovision Song Contest with the song "Everybody" performed by Tanel Padar, Dave Benton, and 2XL. They received 198 points and were the first former Soviet Union country to win. Tanel had previously provided backing vocals for Estonia's 2000 entry. The song was succeeded by Sahlene's "Runaway" in 2002.

In Board of Education v. Earls, the Supreme Court ruled that public schools can legally require drug testing for students participating in extracurricular activities, despite a legal challenge brought by Lindsay Earls, Daniel James, and their families who argued that the policy violated the Fourth Amendment.

The OMD Singles is a compilation album by Orchestral Manoeuvres in the Dark that reached No. 16 in the UK charts. Originally, it was supposed to have a second disc of new remixes, but budget limitations led to the idea being scrapped. The few remixes that were made were released separately as The OMD Remixes. The album was reissued in France in 2003 with the remix disc finally included, along with additional remixes. That same year, Virgin released a two-disc box set that included The OMD Singles and Navigation: The OMD B-Sides.
Mitra gracilefragum is a type of sea snail belonging to the family Mitridae.

Phoenix Air is a non-scheduled airline based in Cartersville, Georgia, USA, founded in 1978. It offers worldwide charter flights for corporate, military, or air ambulance purposes, and employs over 200 skilled workers from Cartersville and the Atlanta metro area.
Ulapes is a town and municipality located in the northwestern region of Argentina's La Rioja Province.

Candonidae is a family of ostracods that includes 25% of all known freshwater ostracod species. Most of the genera in the family are only found in one zoogeographic region, and there are over 500 species, with over 300 of them being exclusive to the Palaearctic ecozone.

Andrea Lilio, also known as L'Anconitano, was an Italian painter who worked mainly in Ancona and Rome during the 17th century. He was employed by Pope Sixtus V to decorate the Vatican library and the Scala Santa in San Giovanni Laterano. Lilio painted in a Mannerist style and created allegories for aristocratic audiences. He died in Ascoli Piceno and painted masterpieces such as The Archangel Michael driving fallen angels from Heaven and the Martyrdom of Saint Lawrence. He also contributed to the painting of the Sistine chapel and painted a picture of All Saints for the cathedral of Fano. Four new allegorical paintings by Lilio were found in Milan's Bagatti Valsecchi Museum.

Paul Smith is a former Scottish football player and manager who played for Raith Rovers, Motherwell, Dunfermline Athletic, Falkirk, Heart of Midlothian, Ayr United, and Berwick Rangers. He became the manager of Berwick Rangers in 1997 and held the position until 2004, during which he got the club promoted to the Scottish Second Division. He later worked as an assistant manager for Stenhousemuir and currently works as an assistant manager for Raith Rovers. Smith was known as "Smudger" during his playing career and had a successful striking partnership with Keith Wright at Raith Rovers.

CUSOM is a private medical school for osteopathic medicine in Lillington, North Carolina, and is one of seven schools at Campbell University. It has provisional accreditation from the American Osteopathic Association's Commission on Osteopathic College Accreditation. Graduates receive a D.O. degree and the first class began rotations in 2013 in underserved areas of North Carolina.

The Qatari-Bahraini War occurred in the Persian Gulf from 1867 to 1868, with Bahrain and Abu Dhabi fighting against Qatar in violation of a maritime truce from 1835. British intervention led to a mediated truce and recognition of Qatar's Al Thani royal family as semi-independent rulers, but both countries suffered significant damage.

Vasilij Kvachantiradze was a skilled Soviet sniper in World War II, with at least 215 confirmed kills of German officers and soldiers during the Vitebsk-Orsha Offensive and a total of around 534 confirmed kills during Operation Bagration or the war.
Stefan Beese, a German production designer and architect, founded beesign in Los Angeles after moving to the United States in 1999.

Lynn Anderson's 1975 album, "I've Never Loved Anyone More," produced by her husband Glenn Sutton, includes 11 tracks and two singles: the title track and "He Turns It Into Love Again." The album features two cover versions, "Faithless Love" and "I'm Not Lisa," and was not released on cassette tape. The title track reached No. 14 on the charts, while "He Turns It Into Love Again" reached No. 13, breaking Anderson's streak of consecutive top ten singles. The title track was originally released by Linda Hargrove in 1974.

Schizaea rupestris is a small fern found in ranges near Sydney, as well as near Woolgoolga and Western Australia. It has mat-shaped infertile fronds that are 5-12 cm high and 1-2.5 mm wide, and rarer fertile fronds that are 8-20 cm high with a tiny reproductive growth. It is found in moist areas such as near waterfalls or shaded areas of sandstone shelves or caves. The name Schizaea comes from the Greek word for "to cleave or split" and rupestris means near rocks. It was first described in 1810 by Robert Brown.

Gayton Pickman Osgood was a Massachusetts-born lawyer and politician who graduated from Harvard University in 1815. He served in the Massachusetts House of Representatives and was elected to the United States House of Representatives as a Jacksonian in 1833. He was not re-elected in 1834 and retired from public life to focus on agriculture. Osgood died in Andover in 1861 and was buried in the Old North Parish Burying Ground.
Phaeotomasellia is a type of fungus in the class Dothideomycetes, but its connection to other types in the class is uncertain. It is a genus with only one species, Phaeotomasellia ruwenzorensis.
Saint Eustace of Luxeuil was the second abbot of Luxeuil from 611, succeeding his teacher Saint Columbanus, and had previously been the head of the monastic school.

Austin Wayne Self is a professional American stock car racing driver who competes full-time in the NASCAR Camping World Truck Series for Win-Tron Racing, driving the No. 22 Toyota Tundra. He has also competed in the ARCA Racing Series, driving the No. 33 Toyota for Win-Tron Racing in February 2016.

Joey Scarallo, an Australian professional racing driver, moved to the United States with his family to expand their wheel business when he was young. Although he currently resides in New York state, he still considers Australia his home.

Hemioniscus balani is a parasitic castrator of barnacles found in the north Atlantic Ocean and the Pacific coast of North America. Its range extends from Norway to Massachusetts and it is uncertain if the Pacific and Atlantic populations are the same species.

Haris Mohammed Hassan is an Iraqi football midfielder who played for Iraq in the 1986 FIFA World Cup and for Al-Rasheed Club. He was a skilled right-sided attacking midfielder who honed his skills on the streets of Mosul. He played for the school province football team and earned a reputation as a goalscorer with the Iraqi youth team. He had the most success while at Al-Rasheed, winning three leagues, two cups, and a record three Arab Club Championships. He was part of the Iraqi team that won the 1982 Asian Cup and played for Iraq in the 1984 Olympics and the 1986 World Cup. He currently works as a pundit for Al Jazeera Sports.

The Estadio Municipal de Vecindario is a stadium in Santa Lucía de Tirajana, Spain, primarily used for football matches and home to UD Vecindario. It can hold up to 4,500 people and has a pitch size of 101x64m. In 2006, it became the first Spanish professional football stadium with artificial turf when Vecindario was promoted to Segunda División.

Christen Schmidt was a Norwegian bishop who was born in Kongsvinger in 1727. He became a vicar in Denmark in 1759 and was appointed Bishop of the Diocese of Oslo in 1773. He was known for being orthodox and supported the death penalty in 1777. He was married twice, first to his cousin Petronelle Lemmich and then to Ingeborg Catharina Birkenbusch.

Rory Duncan, a former South African rugby player, played for Sharks, Mighty Elephants, Free State Cheetahs, and Yamaha Júbilo before retiring in 2011. He later became a coach for Free State Cheetahs' Vodacom Cup and Under-21 teams after coaching at Grey High School.

The Church of St. George is a Macedonian Orthodox church in Staro Nagoričane, known for its impressive architecture and frescoes. It is a significant example of Christian heritage from the 14th century.

Harmonia Caelestis is a collection of 55 sacred cantatas written by Hungarian composer Paul I, 1st Prince Esterházy of Galántha in 1711. They are in the Baroque style and feature Hungarian and German melodies. Each cantata has one movement and is composed for solo voices, choir, and orchestra. Péter Esterházy's novel Harmonia Caelestis is named after the composition.
At the 1972 Summer Olympics, the men's sabre was one of eight fencing events. 53 fencers from 22 countries participated in the competition, which took place from August 30 to 31.
Valery Salov, a Russian chess grandmaster born in Poland on May 26, 1964, was formerly ranked as the third best player globally.

The Moroccan Goumiers were native soldiers who served in auxiliary units attached to the French Army of Africa from 1908 to 1956. They were initially employed as tribal irregulars and later in regular contingents. They served in Morocco, Italy, France, and Indochina during World War II and beyond.
Alikhan Isayevich Nakotskhoyev was a Russian football player who played for FC Angusht Nazran in the Russian Second Division before his death in 2012.

Jackson Waters was a Christian pop rock band that relocated from Arkansas to Nashville in 2005 and signed with Word Records. They released their debut album Come Undone in 2007 and had two songs featured on One Tree Hill. The band went on an indefinite break in 2009, and lead singer David Leonard joined NEEDTOBREATHE as a touring member. Other members are currently pursuing their own projects, with Toby Friesen joining Jeremy Camp's band in 2011.
Temper's "No Favors" topped the Billboard disco/dance chart for a week in 1984 and reached #64 on the R&B chart. It was created by Cleveland Wright III and Anthony Malloy.

Hugh Vincent McGeehan was a football player and coach who served as the head coach at Villanova University for one season in 1923, with a record of 0-7-1. His brother, Charles McGeehan, was also a head football coach at Villanova in 1912.
Real Madrid CF won the 44th King's Cup final on 9 June 1946, defeating Valencia CF 3-1 at Montjuïc in Barcelona.

William Alexander Campbell was a lock for the Australian Wallabies from 1984 to 1990, playing 26 test matches and vice-captaining for 15. He also played for the Queensland Reds, captaining 26 times and winning 21 matches. He was named one of the top 100 Wallabies by Peter Jenkins. Campbell retired from rugby at 29 to pursue medical studies and focus on his family.
Partus Press, situated in Reykjavík, Iceland, is an autonomous publisher of fiction, short-stories, and poetry.

Debbie Millman is a multi-talented American writer, educator, artist, and designer. She is best known for hosting the 'Design Matters' podcast and has been the 'President of Design' at Sterling Brands since 1995, working with major brands. She also chairs the 'Masters in Branding' program at the School of Visual Arts, is the Editorial & Creative Director of Print, a blogger for Fast Company, and the 'President Emeritus' of AIGA.

Turhan Përmeti was an Albanian politician who served as Governor of Crete and ambassador in Saint Petersburg in the Ottoman Empire. He later became Prime Minister of Albania twice, but was criticized for not being familiar with the needs of Albanians due to his lack of affiliation with the Albanian national cause. His premiership was interrupted twice by Albanian discontent.
Aleksandra Drejgier, a female track cyclist from Poland, participated in the team sprint event at the 2009 and 2010 UCI Track Cycling World Championships as a member of the national team.
The Lao Premier League is the top football league in Laos and consists of 14 clubs, expanded from 11 in 2015 for the 2016 season.

KXPA is a radio station in Seattle that is part of the Multicultural Radio Broadcasting network. It is one of 30 stations owned by Arthur Liu that caters to minority and immigrant communities with programs in their native languages. The station has had various formats over the years, including jazz, rock, and country, before adopting an all-advice talk format and eventually settling on its current multicultural format.
NGC 210, a barred spiral galaxy, was found in the constellation Cetus by William Herschel on October 3, 1785 and included in the New General Catalogue.

Kingsley McGowan is an American rugby player for the United States national team and Trinity in Dublin. He plays various positions in the backs, including wing and center. McGowan started playing rugby in high school and played for the U.S. national under-20 team. He attended St. Mary's in California, where he was an All-American and helped win the 2014 D1A national championship.

Bradley Fanelon Jennings is a former American football linebacker who played for Florida State. He was a highly rated high school player and an All-Conference linebacker in college. However, he was shot just before the 2002 NFL Draft and never played professionally. He later became a high school football coach but was charged with aggravated assault in 2009 after a failed robbery attempt, which he claimed was a prank.
Bianor is a type of jumping spider in the Salticidae family that measures 3-4 mm in size.

Don Concannon was a British Labour Party politician who was born in Doncaster, West Riding of Yorkshire. He worked as a miner and served as a councillor on Mansfield Borough Council before being elected as Member of Parliament for Mansfield in 1966. He served as a Government whip and as Northern Ireland minister under Harold Wilson and James Callaghan. Concannon retired from politics due to a car accident and passed away in Mansfield in 2003 at the age of 73.
Amal Hamrouni, born in 1995, is a Tunisian handball player who plays for Club Africain and the Tunisian national team. She competed in the 2015 World Women's Handball Championship.
The Synthetonychiidae is a New Zealand-exclusive family of harvestman with few species in one genus.

The saffron-billed sparrow is a bird species in the Emberizidae family and is found in Argentina, Bolivia, Brazil, and Paraguay. It lives in subtropical or tropical dry forests and subtropical or tropical moist lowland forests.

The National Assembly Members were elected on September 16, 1935, under the Tydings-McDuffie Act that created the Commonwealth of the Philippines. The ruling party leaders, Manuel Quezon and Sergio Osmeña, joined forces for the presidential election, but their supporters formed two distinct parties, the Democraticos and the Democrata Pro-Independencias, during the National Assembly elections. The National Assembly became a unicameral legislature after the Senate was abolished.

Jasper and the Haunted House is a 1942 Puppetoon short film by George Pal, featuring the Paramount characters Jasper, Professor Scarecrow, and Blackbird. It is included in 50 Classic Cartoons Volume 3.

The NPP is a conservative political party in Hong Kong that supports Beijing and was founded by Regina Ip in 2011. It has been suggested that the party was created to help Ip become Chief Executive of Hong Kong. The NPP absorbed Civil Force in 2014 and currently holds three seats in the Legislative Council and 26 seats in the District Councils after the 2016 election.

Kutlug I Bilge Peilo Kagan, also known as Qutlugh Bilge Köl Kaghan, was the ruler of the Uyghur Khaganate from 744 to 747 AD. He was a leader of the Uigur confederation and was elected as Kaghan after an alliance of Basmyls, Uigurs, and Karluks overthrew the ruling Ashina clan.

Lowell Potter Dawson, also known as "Red," was an American football coach who worked at the University of Pittsburgh and Tulane University at the college level, as well as the Buffalo Bills in the professional level of the AAFC. He was trained in football coaching by Bernie Bierman at the University of Minnesota. Dawson's most successful coaching experiences were with Tulane and Buffalo, where his 1939 Tulane team went undefeated before losing to Texas A&M in the Sugar Bowl, and his 1948 Buffalo Bills team won the AAFC Eastern Division title but lost the championship game to the Cleveland Browns. Dawson's final record was 36-19-4 at Tulane, 9-11-1 at Pitt, and 19-25-4 at Buffalo.

Zhu Bo is a former Chinese football player and current manager who played as a right-back for Bayi Football Team and ended his career with Shenzhen Feiyada. He has coached several clubs in the Chinese football league divisions, including Hunan Xiangjun, Yunnan Lijiang Dongba, Nanchang Bayi, Changsha Ginde F.C., Shenzhen Fengpeng, and Yinchuan Helanshan.

The Swiss National Library is responsible for collecting and preserving information related to Switzerland in all forms and making it widely accessible. It aims to reflect the diversity of Swiss culture and is undergoing modernization to become a national information center.
Scott M. Gimple is a writer for television and comics, recognized for his contributions to Fillmore!, Life, FlashForward, Chase, and The Walking Dead as a writer and producer.

John Charles Frémont was an American military officer, explorer, and politician who was the first candidate of the anti-slavery Republican Party for the office of President of the United States. He led four expeditions into the American West during the 1840s and was known as The Pathfinder. Frémont took control of California during the Mexican-American War and proclaimed himself military Governor of California, but was convicted in court martial for mutiny and insubordination. He became one of the first two U.S. senators elected from the new state of California in 1850 and was the first presidential candidate of the new Republican Party, but lost the 1856 presidential election to Democrat James Buchanan. During the American Civil War, he was given command of Department of the West by President Abraham Lincoln, but was relieved of his command for insubordination. Frémont's wealth declined after investing heavily and purchasing an unsuccessful Pacific Railroad in 1866. He served as Governor of Arizona appointed by President Rutherford B. Hayes and died in New York City in 1890.
SH 256 is a Texas state highway that stretches from Silverton in the north to a junction with US 83 near Wellington, near the Oklahoma border.

P.T. Barnum was an American showman, businessman, and politician known for promoting hoaxes and founding the Barnum & Bailey Circus. He started as a small-business owner and founded a weekly newspaper before moving to New York City in 1834. He used his museum to promote hoaxes and human curiosities, and later promoted the American tour of singer Jenny Lind. After economic reversals, he used a lecture tour to emerge from debt. He served two terms in the Connecticut legislature and was elected as Mayor of Bridgeport, where he worked to improve the water supply and enforce laws. He is most famous for his traveling circus, menagerie, and museum of "freaks". He died in 1891 and was buried in Mountain Grove Cemetery, Bridgeport.

Pierre Gauthier was a Canadian politician who served as a member of the Canadian House of Commons for both the Liberal party and the Bloc populaire. He was born in Deschambault, Quebec and became a physician after studying at various institutions. Gauthier entered provincial politics in 1927 and was later elected to the federal government in 1936. He briefly left the Liberals to join the Bloc populaire in 1943 but returned to the Liberals in 1945. Gauthier served in Parliament until his defeat in 1958.

The Toprakkale-Iskendurun railway is a 58.9 km electrified railway in southern Turkey that branches off the Adana-Nusaybin railway at Toprakkale and services the Port of Iskendurun and Isdemir steel mill. It is an important freight route for iron ore from mines near Divriği and is owned and operated by the Turkish State Railways.
The Megasoma elephas is a Neotropical rhinoceros beetle belonging to the Scarabaeidae family and Dynastinae subfamily.

Gabriele Tarquini is an Italian racing driver who participated in 78 Formula One Grands Prix, scoring 1 championship point and holding the record for the most failed attempts to qualify. He has since won the BTCC in 1994, the ETCC in 2003, and the WTCC in 2009, becoming the oldest ever world champion in an FIA series at the age of 47 years and 266 days.
Roberto Manini, who was born in Milan on January 11, 1942, is a former Italian footballer.
Melanie Faisst, a German ski jumper born on February 12, 1990 in Titisee-Neustadt, made her World Cup debut on December 3, 2011 in Lillehammer, Norway and placed third.

Gifford Pinchot III is an American entrepreneur and author who co-founded Pinchot University, formerly known as Bainbridge Graduate Institute. He is credited with inventing the concept of intrapreneurship in a 1978 paper he wrote with his wife, Elizabeth Pinchot. Their book, Intrapreneuring: Why You Don't Have to Leave the Corporation to Become an Entrepreneur, expanded on this concept and sparked discussion in management. Pinchot is also the grandson of Gifford Pinchot, the first Chief of the United States Forest Service and 28th Governor of Pennsylvania, and has continued his grandfather's work in conservationism.

James Whitney Dunn is a Michigan politician and businessman who served in the U.S. House of Representatives from 1981 to 1983, ran for Senate in 1988 but lost, and lost in the primary for another term in the U.S. House in 1990.
Michael Joseph Murphy was a Catholic bishop who served as the Bishop of Erie, Pennsylvania from 1982 to 1990.

In 1970, the 95th Preakness Stakes race had a prize of $205,000 and was won by Personality, ridden by Eddie Belmonte, who beat My Dad George by a neck. The race was televised on CBS and had a total attendance of 42,474, making it the third most attended American thoroughbred racing event in North America that year.
Borrelia hermsii can infect Ornithodoros hermsi, a type of soft tick.
Marina Anatolyevna Antipova, a Russian ice dancer born in 1992, won three ISU Junior Grand Prix silver medals and a 2009 Russian junior bronze medal with her former partner Artem Kudashev.

Arisa Noto is a Japanese voice actress and singer who is affiliated with Style Cube. She has been a member of StylipS, Ongaku Gatas, and Hello! Project. Additionally, she works as a performance motion actor, dancer, and choreographer for anime, anison artist, and video games.

Uarbryichthys, a type of ancient teleost fish, lived in lakes near the Talbragar River Bed during the Upper Jurassic period in Australia. It is closely related to macrosemiids and had a heterocercal tail fin, giving it a similar appearance to a small sea bream.
Edgecumbe College is the sole secondary school in Edgecumbe, New Zealand, catering to students from Year 9 to Year 13, with a roll of 213 as of late 2014.
Evelyn Boscawen was a British Army officer and 7th Viscount Falmouth.
Mohammad Ali Samatar, a Somali politician and Lieutenant General, was a key member of the Supreme Revolutionary Council and served as Somalia's Prime Minister from 1987 to 1990.
Ivan Radović, a Serbian tennis player and painter, was born on June 22, 1894 in Vršac and died on August 14, 1973 in Belgrade.

Marc McNulty, a Scottish footballer, currently plays as a striker for Bradford City on loan from Sheffield United. He began his career playing for various Scottish youth teams before signing with Livingston at 16 years old. After playing over 100 games for Livingston, he joined Sheffield United in 2014.
Viscardi Andrade Guimarães is a Brazilian MMA fighter competing in the Welterweight division of the UFC.

Maleme is a small village and military airport in northwestern Crete, Greece, located 16 km west of Chania. It has many large hotels, pleasant apartments, bars, and cafés close to the beach. Visitors can discover the German Cemetery, the historical Minoan tomb, and a traditional ceramics workshop. Maleme also has a variety of shops with local products and a large supermarket. A bus stop across the street leads to Chania city center and other areas.
The 2008 New Progressive Party primaries determined the PNP's nominees for political offices in Puerto Rico, including Governor. Luis Fortuño won the primary and went on to win the general election.
Robert Joe McCreary, born in 1939, played as an offensive tackle for the Dallas Cowboys in the NFL and the Calgary Stampeders in the CFL after playing college football at Wake Forest University.

Joe 'Dodo' Winston, a former Gaelic footballer for Naomh Adhamhnáin and the Donegal senior football team, played on several Donegal teams in the 1970s, including the 1972 and 1974 Ulster Senior Football Championship-winning teams. He later served as assistant manager for the 1987 All-Ireland Under 21 Football Championship-winning team. He is married to Mary and has two sons, Kevin and Darren, and a daughter, Elaine, who passed away in 2012.

Toni Nadal, a Spanish tennis coach born in Manacor, Mallorca, is the uncle and coach of Rafael Nadal and the older brother of Miguel Ángel Nadal. He holds the record for the most Grand Slam titles won by a coach, with 14 trophies won with Rafael Nadal as of 2013.
Manuel Guijarro Doménech, a retired Spanish cyclist, participated in the 1989 Tour de France and Vuelta a España.

Aldo Rossi was an Italian architect and designer who gained global recognition in theory, drawing, architecture, and product design. He was the first Italian to win the Pritzker Prize for architecture.

The Qatar Bahrain Causeway, a planned bridge between the two Arab states, was announced in 2008 with a cost of $2.3 billion. However, as of June 2015, construction had not started and the project was on hold. Bahrain's Foreign Minister stated in 2011 that the bridge was important for both countries' economic growth. An anonymous source announced in 2011 that construction would start that year and be completed by 2015 at a cost of $5 billion. By 2012, the Foreign Minister stated that the bridge would only be completed before the 2022 FIFA World Cup due to financial turbulence.

Caitlin Van Zandt played Ashlee Wolfe on Guiding Light from 2006 to 2009. Ashlee faced challenges due to her weight and tried to overcome them by dating Henry Cooper Bradshaw. Van Zandt's own lap-band surgery influenced Ashlee's storyline and garnered media attention for promoting healthy habits.

Dave Bennett, an Irish hurler born in 1976, played as a midfielder for the Waterford senior team from 1994-2008, winning two Munster medals and becoming an All-Ireland runner-up. He also won a county championship medal with Lismore at club level.

Destiny is a first-person shooter video game developed by Bungie and published by Activision. It was released in 2014 for PlayStation and Xbox consoles and features a multiplayer environment with elements of role-playing games. Players take on the role of a Guardian defending Earth's last safe city from alien threats. The game has received mixed to positive reviews and has had four expansion packs released since its launch. It sold over US$500 million on its first day of release and was awarded GamesRadar's 2014 Game of the Year and the BAFTA Award for Best Game.
The Church of England's Holy Trinity Church in Kirk Ireton, Derbyshire is a Grade I listed parish church.

The Sapling Stakes is an annual horse race for 2-year-olds held in September at Monmouth Park in New Jersey. It was originally run on dirt over 6 furlongs, but in 2014 the distance was changed to 1 mile. The race was first held in 1883, but was banned in 1894 due to betting laws. It was revived in 1946 and has since been run in two divisions. The purse has been reduced to $100,000 and it was downgraded to a Listed Status in 2014.

The Kaniv Hydroelectric Power Plant in Ukraine is operated by Ukrhydroenego, a part of the Energy Company of Ukraine. The plant was designed by UkrHydroProject and constructed by specialized companies, with turbines from Turboatom and generators from Elektrovazhmash. The dam includes a lock for water travel along the Dnieper river. Renovations were completed in two stages, with funding from the IBRD and the World Bank and the Ukrainian government.
Siphonaria diemenensis is a type of marine snail that breathes air and belongs to the family Siphonariidae, also known as false limpets.

The Clarkson Covered Bridge is a wooden covered bridge in Cullman County, Alabama that spans Crooked Creek. It was built in 1904 and is a Town Lattice truss construction over four spans. The bridge is 270 feet long and is located at Clarkson Covered Bridge Park. It was listed on the National Register of Historic Places in 1974 and is currently the second-longest covered bridge in Alabama. The Cullman County Commission maintains the bridge.
Maurice Farrell, a former Irish footballer, is recognized for his 13-year tenure as a left back with Bray Wanderers in the League of Ireland.
Jerry Baldwin, an American entrepreneur, co-founded Starbucks in Seattle in 1971 with Gordon Bowker and Zev Siegl.

Montgomery Gentry is a country music duo consisting of Eddie Montgomery and Troy Gentry. They have released eight studio albums, four compilation albums, one extended play, and twenty-six singles. The duo has had five Number One singles and ten additional Top Ten singles, all of which have crossed over to the Billboard Hot 100. Three of their albums are certified platinum and three are certified gold by the RIAA.

Megavalanche is a mountain bike downhill marathon event that starts at the summit of Pic Blanc in the French Alps and ends in Allemont. The event consists of three main days: practice, qualifying, and Megavalanche. The top 25 riders from each qualifier start the Megavalanche, while the following 25 riders participate in the Mega Challenger. The remaining riders are grouped into the Mega Amateur and Affinity groups. The event attracts around 2,700 participants from mainland Europe and the UK, and other rounds take place in Peru and Reunion Island.

Isabel Martínez de Perón, the third wife of President Juan Perón, served as both vice president and First Lady during her husband's third term as president of Argentina from 1973 to 1974. After her husband's death in office, she became the first female president of any country in the world from 1 July 1974 to 24 March 1976. In 2007, she was arrested in Spain over the forced disappearance of an activist in February 1976, but Spanish courts refused her extradition to Argentina.
The following is a compilation of Mexican football transfers during the 2012-13 winter transfer window, categorized by club and limited to Liga MX, the top tier of Mexican football.

On June 10, 1979, Belgium held elections for the European Parliament, resulting in the election of 13 MEPs by the Dutch-speaking electoral college and 11 MEPs by the French-speaking electoral college.

The Moesa is a 47 km river that runs through Graubünden and Ticino in Switzerland, and is a tributary of the Ticino. It originates in Val Vignun near the San Bernardino Pass and flows through Val Mesolcina towards Roveredo, where it meets the rivers Calancasca and Traversagna. It eventually flows into the Ticino near Arbedo-Castione and is a well-liked spot for kayaking.

Godfrey Binaisa was a Ugandan lawyer who served as Attorney General from 1962 to 1968 and as President from June 1979 to May 1980. He was the only surviving former president of Uganda at the time of his death.

The asteroid 260 Huberta is a dark, carbon-rich member of the Cybele group, located near the outer edge of the Main belt. It may have been caught in a 4:7 orbital resonance with Jupiter and was discovered by Johann Palisa in 1886 and named after Saint Hubertus.
Daniel Biles is a Justice on the Kansas Supreme Court who was appointed by Governor Kathleen Sebelius on January 7, 2009, to replace Chief Justice Kay McFarland.

DMG Media, a part of Daily Mail and General Trust, publishes Metro, a free tabloid newspaper in the UK. It is distributed on weekdays (excluding bank holidays) on public transport and stations, and distributors also hand out copies to pedestrians.

In 2003, Iced Earth released the single "The Reckoning" featuring three tracks from their album "The Glorious Burden". The album's release was delayed due to the departure of lead singer Matt Barlow, so the record company released the single to fill the gap. The single was the first to feature lead vocalist Tim "Ripper" Owens and included softer tracks to increase radio airplay. A music video was filmed for the title-track and an unplugged version of "When the Eagle Cries" was only released on the single and limited edition of the album.
Samiullah Agha, born on January 1, 1981, is a Pakistani cricketer who played for the Quetta team in first-class cricket.

The Arctic Race of Norway is a yearly cycling competition in northern Norway, organized by ASO and AS. It began in 2013 and lasts for four days. It is a UCI-sponsored event and was initially rated as a 2.1 event, but from 2015 it was rated as a 2.HC event.
Jaco Mostert is a Namibian artistic gymnast who competes internationally, including at the 2003 World Artistic Gymnastics Championships in Anaheim, United States.
Żoruchowo, located in the Pomeranian Voivodeship of Poland, is a railway station that is no longer in use by PKP.
U Television Sdn. Bhd. is Malaysia's third pay television operator, launched on September 5, 2005, with 40 channels from global content providers after obtaining necessary censorship board approvals.
Abdelsalam al-Majali, a Jordanian physician and politician, was the prime minister of Jordan twice.

Tales from the Brothers Gibb: A History in Song is a compilation box set by The Bee Gees, released in 1990. It includes their music from 1967 to 1989, arranged into four chapters representing different periods of their career. The set features B-sides, solo material, unreleased tracks, and live performances, with some songs receiving new stereo mixes. The packaging includes song symbols, photos from 1989, and comments from one of the brothers on each song in the accompanying book.

Sir William Ewart was an Irish linen manufacturer and Unionist politician who served in the House of Commons from 1878 until his death in 1889. He was also a magistrate for Antrim and Belfast, president of the Irish Linen Trade Association, and mayor of Belfast in 1859. He was created a baronet in 1887 and married Isaella Kelso Mathewson.

Guto ap Owain Bebb is a Welsh Conservative Party politician and the MP for Aberconwy. He was elected in 2010 and is a member of the Conservative Friends of Israel group. He was appointed Parliamentary Under Secretary of State at the Wales Office and a Government Whip on 19 March 2016.

Jessie Evans, the former head men's basketball coach at the University of San Francisco, was replaced by Eddie Sutton in 2007. Prior to this, he held the same position at the University of Louisiana at Lafayette. In 2012, he became an assistant men's basketball coach at Southeast Missouri State University.
Born in 1955, Rumiko Ukai is a Japanese voice actress who is famous for her role as Frau Bow in the original Mobile Suit Gundam. She is affiliated with 81 Produce.
Raymond George Hamilton was an Australian Labor Party member who served in the New South Wales Legislative Assembly from 1941 to 1950.

Crowded House, a British-bred Thoroughbred racehorse and sire, won two of his four races as a two-year-old in 2008, including the Group One Racing Post Trophy. He was a leading contender for the British Classic Races in 2009 but performed poorly in the Dante Stakes and finished sixth in the Epsom Derby. He never won another race but finished second in the Al Maktoum Challenge, Round 2 and the Pacific Classic. He retired from racing in 2011 and became a breeding stallion in Australia.

Hong Kong Tramways is a tram system in Hong Kong that has been in operation for over 110 years. It is owned and operated by Veolia Transport RATP Asia and runs on Hong Kong Island between Shau Kei Wan and Kennedy Town, with a branch through Happy Valley. The tram system is a major tourist attraction and is the only one in the world operated exclusively with double-decker trams. It is also one of only three non-heritage tram systems in the world that use double-deck cars. The tram is the cheapest mode of public transport on the island, with a fare of $2.3.
Norwegian ski mountaineer Ole-Jakob Sande participated in the 2008 World Championship of Ski Mountaineering relay event and finished in seventh place with his team.

Joseph William Colborne is a Canadian ice hockey forward who currently plays for the Colorado Avalanche in the NHL. He was drafted by the Boston Bruins in the first round of the 2008 NHL Entry Draft but was later traded to the Toronto Maple Leafs in 2011. He then joined the Calgary Flames in 2013 before signing with the Avalanche in 2016.

The Journal of Strategic Studies, established in 1978, is a bi-monthly publication featuring articles on military and diplomatic strategy. It is edited by Dr. Joe Maiolo and Thomas G. Mahnken and has an impact factor of 0.944, ranking it 57th out of 161 journals in Political Science and 31st out of 85 journals in International Relations.

Claudia Beni performed "Više nisam tvoja" in both Croatian and English at Eurovision 2003, with the English version titled "I Can't be Your Lover". The song received 29 points and placed 15th out of 26. Claudia wore a colored dress and was lifted into the air by her backing singers at the end of the performance. The song is an up-tempo breakup anthem. It was succeeded by "You Are The Only One" in 2004.

Olli Kortekangas composed Seven Songs for Planet Earth in 2011 for the Choral Arts Society of Washington and the Tampere Philharmonic Orchestra. It premiered at the Kennedy Center in Washington D.C. on May 22, 2011 and was conducted by Norman Scribner. The piece also had a second performance on May 19, 2011 in San Francisco, conducted by Robert Geary.
The shining drongo is a bird species in the Dicruridae family, inhabiting subtropical or tropical moist lowland forests in countries such as Cameroon, Ghana, and the Democratic Republic of the Congo.

Radio Havana Cuba is Cuba's official international broadcasting station, which can be heard globally on shortwave and other frequencies, as well as through free-to-air satellite and internet streaming alongside other Cuban radio and television broadcasts.

Josep Gonzalvo, also known as Gonzalvo II, was a Spanish Catalan footballer and coach who played for FC Barcelona, Spain, and the Catalan XI. His brothers, Gonzalvo I and Gonzalvo III, were also notable footballers. After retiring as a player, he briefly managed Barcelona before passing away in 1978.
The Portugal National Championship for ice hockey was held only during the 2000-01 season and took place exclusively at the Palácio do Gelo in Viseu.

Staurois is a small genus of true frogs, mostly found in Borneo with two species in the Philippines. They are ancient members of the Ranidae family and are known as splash or foot-flagging frogs due to their behavior of waving their hindlegs and feet to signal others. This behavior is also seen in other frog genera like Hylodes and Micrixalus.

Paola Laura Ruggeri Ghigo, born in Caracas, Venezuela on July 14, 1961, was crowned Miss Venezuela 1983 and was the only Latin American to make it to the Top 12 semifinalists in Miss Universe 1983, finishing in 7th place.
WEXP, a college radio station in Philadelphia, used to broadcast on 1600 kHz AM before transitioning to an Internet-only format. It has a freeform radio style.

The Mint Chicks, a New Zealand band that combined experimental noise rock and power pop, were active from 2001 to 2010. They were based in Auckland and later in Portland, USA, and won multiple New Zealand Music Awards. They released three studio albums, four EPs, and 17 singles.

Doctor Shameless is a two-episode hentai anime based on an eroge about Dr. Shinji. It was released on two DVDs in Japan in 2003 and in the United States by Kitty Media on March 25, 2003. It was also released in Spanish by Llamentol and in German by Trimax.

The Archdiocese of Messina was initially a diocese but became an archdiocese in 1986 after merging with the former Diocese of Lipari and the Territorial Prelature of Santa Lucia del Mela, with the Diocese of Patti and Diocese of Nicosia as suffragans.

Agkistrodon piscivorus is a venomous pit viper found in the southeastern United States, known for its painful and potentially fatal bite. It is the only semiaquatic viper and is usually found in or near water. Its scientific name translates to "hooked-tooth fish-eater" and it has several common names, including water moccasin and cottonmouth.

Tom Riley served as the US Ambassador to Morocco for five years, receiving the Grand Cross of the Order of Ouissam Alaouite from King Mohammed VI. He was also awarded the State Department's 2009 Sue M. Cobb Award for Exemplary Diplomatic Service. Prior to his ambassadorship, he was Senior VP and Managing Director International for Savvis, Inc. until February 2011.

Jue Wang, a Chinese pianist born in Shanghai on March 5, 1984, has achieved great success in Spanish piano competitions, winning first prizes in both Barcelona's 51st Maria Canals and Santander's 16th Paloma O'Shea competitions, after being trained entirely in China.

Fourteen Hills is a literary magazine published by San Francisco State University's MFA program, featuring poetry, fiction, short plays, and literary nonfiction. It showcases experimental and progressive work by emerging and established writers, including the annual winner of the Michael Rubin Chapbook Award. Several pieces first published in Fourteen Hills have won prestigious literary awards.

Noboribetsu Station is a railway station in Noboribetsu, Hokkaido, Japan, assigned the station number H28. It was opened on August 1, 1892, and serves as a gateway to the Noboribetsu Onsen hot spring, which is a 15-minute ride away by Dōnan Bus.
Burg Scharfenstein, a ruined castle in Hesse, Germany, was built in 1160 under Christian I as part of the Bishopric of Mainz's border fortifications.
Myrmarachne paludosa is a Sri Lankan spider belonging to the Myrmarachne genus.
George Edwin Bowden, the nephew of Lemuel Jackson Bowden, served as a U.S. Representative from Virginia from July 6, 1852 to January 22, 1908.

Ośno Drugie is a village located in Gmina Aleksandrów Kujawski, Aleksandrów County, Kuyavian-Pomeranian Voivodeship, Poland. It is situated 3 km south of Aleksandrów Kujawski and 22 km south of Toruń, with a population of 208.

The Palace Hotel is a residential building located on the east side of City Hall Square in Copenhagen, Denmark. It was designed by Anton Rosen and finished in 1910, with an Art Nouveau influence evident in its red brick construction.

Mozingo Lake Golf Course is an 18-hole municipal golf course in Nodaway County, Missouri, designed by Donald Sechrest and opened in 1995. It is a par 72 course with a rating of 73.5 and a slope rating of 134 on Rye grass. It is owned by the city of Maryville and is considered the best course to play in Missouri for under $50 by Golf Digest and USA Today. The signature hole is #8, a 170-yard, par 3, requiring a tee shot over a pond to the green. A Junior 9 golf course designed by Tom Watson opened in 2016.
Piotr Kuklis, a Polish footballer born on January 14, 1986 in Łódź, is currently a midfielder for Bytovia Bytów.

Duronto Rajshahi was a cricket team in the Bangladesh Premier League representing Rajshahi, Bangladesh. They played in the first two seasons with Simon Katich as captain and Tamim Iqbal as deputy. The team was coached by Khaled Mashud and Athar Ali Khan. They have since been revived as Rajshahi Kings in the 2016 season.

Ed Sneed is an American golfer, sportscaster, and course design consultant who played on the PGA Tour and the Champions Tour. He won four PGA Tour events and was a member of the Ryder Cup team in 1977. Sneed is known for his meltdown in The Masters in 1979, where he lost to Fuzzy Zoeller in a sudden-death playoff. He made his debut on the Champions Tour in 1994 and has worked as a golf broadcaster and course design consultant. He currently lives in Palm Harbor, Florida, and plans to provide golf instruction at Muirfield Village Golf Club in Dublin, Ohio.

Tetsuya Utsumi is a left-handed pitcher for the Yomiuri Giants in Japan's Central League. He gained attention in 2008 when he struck out 4 out of 6 Boston Red Sox batters during an exhibition game. Prior to his baseball career, he worked for Tokyo Gas from 2000 to 2003.

Margrave Rudolf II of Hachberg-Sausenberg succeeded his father and ruled with his brother Otto I. They relocated their government from Sausenburg Castle to Rötteln Castle. In 1332, Basel troops besieged Rötteln Castle due to a conflict with one of the brothers. The issue was resolved through mediation by the nobility.

Nolichucky Dam, maintained by the Tennessee Valley Authority, is a concrete gravity overflow type dam on the Nolichucky River near Greeneville, Tennessee. It impounds Davy Crockett Lake, which has roughly 800 acres of water surface and is used for flood control and recreation. The dam was built in 1912-1913 for hydroelectricity generation and was capable of producing 10,640 kilowatts of electricity until sediment buildup in the lake made continued electricity generation impractical in 1972.
Gadde Ruthvika Shivani, an Indian badminton player born on March 26, 1997, trains at the Gopichand Badminton Academy and competes in Singles.
Breakstep, also known as breakbeat garage, originated from UK garage and had an impact on the development of dubstep.

The 1934 earthquake caused severe damage in the lower North Island, with the strongest shaking felt in Wairarapa, Wellington, and Hawke's Bay. It was felt across much of New Zealand, with destructive intensities of VIII and a peak of IX south-east of Pahiatua. Recent reviews suggest the epicenter was closer to Horoeka.

In 1313, during the First War of Scottish Independence, Sir James Douglas and Walter Stewart successfully captured Roxburgh Castle by disguising their men as cows and surprising the garrison with ladders. The siege was a prelude to the Battle of Bannockburn and the Scots destroyed the castle to prevent the English from regaining control.

Keitai Denjū Telefang is a Japanese RPG video game series developed by Smilesoft and published by Natsume. The player uses a mobile phone-like device to contact creatures and battle foes. The first game was released in 2000 for Game Boy Color in two versions, each with exclusive creatures. The series name comes from the Japanese term for mobile phone and fang. A sequel, Keitai Denjū Telefang 2, was released in 2002 for Game Boy Advance in two versions with similar differences.

Aslina An Ping Chua is a Malaysian tennis player who debuted on the WTA tour at the 2013 Malaysian Open, losing in the first round of both singles and doubles events. She has a 5-6 win-loss record while playing for Malaysia at the Fed Cup.
On August 7, 2012, partisan primaries were held to select nominees for the 2012 Michigan House of Representatives elections, which took place on November 6, 2012.
The Ghanaian women's football league began in 2012-13, following the existence of regional and zonal leagues.
Raphaël Wignanitz is a French male artistic gymnast who competes internationally, including at the 2006 World Artistic Gymnastics Championships in Denmark.

The National Party was a political party in South Africa that governed the country from 1924 to 1994, during which it implemented apartheid policies. It was also known as the Nats and promoted Afrikaner culture. In the 1980s, many of its supporters left for the Conservative Party due to the dismantling of apartheid. After 1990, the party opened up its membership to all races and rebranded itself as a non-racial, conservative force. It was renamed the New National Party in 1997 but was disbanded in 2005.

Fallout 3 has five DLCs that add new missions, locations, and items. Broken Steel has the biggest impact, changing the ending and allowing players to continue past the main quest. The Game of the Year edition includes all DLCs. The DLCs were originally only available on Xbox Live and Games for Windows. The PlayStation 3 version did not have DLCs due to a speculated deal between Microsoft and Bethesda. However, in 2009, Bethesda made three DLCs available for PlayStation 3 and later released all DLCs for all platforms.

In 1985, Wales and Scotland played their final qualifying match for the 1986 FIFA World Cup at Ninian Park. Wales needed to win while Scotland only needed a draw. The game was played amidst concerns of football hooliganism and a potential crackdown by the British government. Despite missing key players, Scotland achieved the draw they needed, eliminating Wales from the competition. Tragically, Scotland's manager Jock Stein collapsed and died in the treatment room after the game.

Volodymyr Oleksandrovych Kaplychnyi was a Soviet football defender who played for FC Dynamo Khmelnitsky, SKA Lviv, and PFC CSKA Moscow. He earned 62 caps for the USSR national football team and participated in UEFA Euro 1968, the 1970 FIFA World Cup, and UEFA Euro 1972. He won a bronze medal at the 1972 Olympics.

The Aura is a river in south-western Finland that flows through several towns before discharging into the Archipelago Sea in Turku. It is 70 kilometers long and contains eleven rapids, with the biggest being Nautelankoski. The river's water is brown due to agricultural runoff, but its condition has improved since the 1970s and it now supports salmon. The river has cultural significance in Finland and has been inhabited for at least 6,000 years. The archdiocese of Finland has been located near the river since the thirteenth century.
Georg Frideric Handel composed a dramatic secular cantata called Allor ch'io dissi addio (HWV 80) for soprano in 1707-08. It is also known as HG l,8 and means "Then I said goodbye".

The Czech Hockey Games is an annual ice hockey event held in the Czech Republic as part of the Euro Hockey Tour. It started in 1994 as the Pragobanka Cup and has had various sponsors, including Česká pojišťovna and Kajotbet. The tournament was played between August and September until 2011 when it was moved to April, except for Winter Olympics years when it's played in September. The tournament has been held in Zlín, Pardubice, and Liberec.
Jo Luck, a former CEO of Heifer International, received a World Food Prize in 2010 as an American.
Psyrassa clavigera belongs to the Cerambycidae family and is a type of beetle.

Terry Milera is an Australian rules footballer who played for St Kilda in the Australian Football League before moving to Glenelg Football Club in the South Australian National Football League. He was recruited by Greater Western Sydney and traded to St Kilda in 2011, where he signed a two-year contract and made his debut in 2012. Milera left St Kilda after the 2014 season to return to his family in South Australia.

Elijah Babbitt was a Republican US Representative from Pennsylvania who was born in Rhode Island and moved to New York with his parents in 1805. He studied law and practiced in Milton before moving to Erie, where he served as attorney for the borough and city, as well as prosecuting attorney for Erie County. Babbitt also served in the Pennsylvania House of Representatives and State Senate before being elected to the Thirty-sixth and Thirty-seventh Congresses. He died in Erie in 1887 and was buried in Erie Cemetery.

Mickey Niblock, a retired Irish Gaelic footballer, played for Derry from 1966 to 1973 and won several championships. He started his club career with O'Donovan Rossa Magherafelt, played for various clubs in the US, and later played for Douglas and Nemo Rangers in County Cork. Niblock was known for his skills and is considered one of Derry's best players.
In 1968, the Supreme Court of the United States declared an Oregon statute unconstitutional for interfering with foreign affairs, despite not conflicting with any federal laws or treaties.

Boyceville Municipal Airport is a public airport owned by the village of Boyceville, Wisconsin, located in the central business district. It is categorized as a basic general aviation facility and has no IATA designation.

Lavington Sports Ground, formerly known as Lavington Panthers Oval, is a sports ground in Hamilton Valley, Albury, Australia with a capacity of around 20,000. It includes a cricket wicket, velodrome, and netball courts, and is home to the Lavington Panthers Football Club. The ground has hosted AFL practice matches in the past, but due to inadequate lighting, the AFL now schedules such fixtures in Narrandera. However, in 2015, Richmond vs Port Adelaide was hosted there. In 2010, AlburyCity upgraded the lighting to television broadcast standards for around $500K.

The 2010 Chicago Bears season saw the team improve on their previous year's record and make their first playoff appearance since 2006. They won the NFC North division and earned a bye as the NFC's second seed. However, their season ended with a loss to the Green Bay Packers in the NFC Championship Game. Despite a winning season in 2012, the Bears have not made the playoffs since.
Kelly Denton, an American stock car racing driver, participated in NASCAR from 1996 to 2002, and was born in Bristol, Virginia on March 10, 1973.

Laurel Park Place is a high-end shopping mall in Livonia, Michigan, managed by CBL & Associates Properties. It has over 70 stores and restaurants, including Carson's and Von Maur. The mall also has a movie theater, food court, Livonia Marriott hotel, and office tower. In 2004, it had sales of $409 per sq ft, making it a class A mall. It is located near I-275 and 6 Mile Rd.

Nathaniel Pendleton was a lawyer and judge during the American Revolutionary War and after. He served in the Continental Army and was Attorney General of Georgia. He was nominated by President George Washington to be a Judge for the United States District Court for the District of Georgia and later became a county judge in New York. He was also a second to Alexander Hamilton in Hamilton's duel with Aaron Burr. His son was Congressman Nathanael Greene Pendleton.

Nashestvie is a large Russian rock festival organized by Nashe Radio station, held annually in July (previously August) near Moscow since 1999 (open air since 2000), except for 2007. The festival has changed locations several times, from Ramenskoye to Tver Oblast. Its name is a play on words meaning "invasion" and is also derived from the name of Nashe Radio. It has been dubbed the "Russian Woodstock" by the media.

Sarbiewo is a village in Poland's Masovian Voivodeship, located 7 km east of Baboszewo and 8 km north of Płońsk. It has a population of 200 and is known for being the birthplace of Maciej Kazimierz Sarbiewski, a famous Latin poet. The village hosts the International Days of Maciej Kazimierz Sarbiewski, a poetry festival.

The 1995 Gulf of Aqaba earthquake, also known as the Nuweiba earthquake, had a magnitude of 7.3 and occurred on November 22 at 06:15 local time. It caused 8 deaths and 30 injuries in the meizoseismal area and was the strongest tectonic event in the area for many decades. The earthquake occurred along the Dead Sea Transform fault system, which has occasional large and damaging earthquakes. It also remotely triggered a series of small to moderate earthquakes 500 kilometers to the north of the epicenter. Investigations were conducted to determine surface faulting and aftershock distribution.

Luis Alberto Falcó was an Argentine physician and politician who served on the Argentine Senate from 2001 until his death in 2007. He was born in General Roca, Río Negro Province, and graduated in medicine at the Catholic University of Córdoba in 1972. Falcó was a prolific legislator, introducing dozens of new laws, including the 'Falcó Law' promoting the use of biofuels. He died in July 2007 after a long illness, and Jacobo Abrameto completed the remaining months of his term on the Senate.

Frank Hampson was a British illustrator who created and drew Dan Dare and other characters in the boys' comic, the Eagle, from 1950 to 1961. He wrote and drew Dan Dare's Venus and Red Moon stories, as well as a complete storyline for Operation Saturn, but only drew part of the Saturn story and his script was changed when he passed the strip to assistants.
BC Prievidza is a Slovakian basketball team that competes in the Slovak Extraliga and plays their home games at the Niké Arena.

The Kolbäck Bridge spans the Ume River in Umeå, Sweden, connecting the island Ön to the mainland on both sides. It is 522 meters long and carries 3 lanes of European route E4, despite being designed for 2. Construction took place from 1998 to 2001.

The Holy Trinity the Less church in Knightrider Street, City of London, was destroyed in the Great Fire of London. A Lutheran church was built on the site after the fire, but it was later demolished in 1871 to make room for Mansion House underground station.

The 2013 AFC Beach Soccer Championship was held in Doha, Qatar from January 22-26, 2013. The tournament was played at a temporary stadium and adjacent pitch on Katara Beach, with a capacity of 3,000 spectators. The top three teams qualified to represent Asia at the 2013 FIFA Beach Soccer World Cup in Papeete, Tahiti.

Wycombe Air Park, also known as Booker Airfield, is a general aviation aerodrome located in Booker, Buckinghamshire, England. It opened in 1941 as RAF Booker and was primarily used for training during WWII. It has a CAA Ordinary Licence and has over 90,000 movements per year, including training circuits. The films 'Those Magnificent Men in their Flying Machines' and 'Aces High' were filmed here.

The River Derg is a 28-mile long river in Ireland that originates from Lough Derg and flows eastward through Castlederg. It joins the River Strule to form the River Mourne and is known for its salmon, grilse, and sea trout. The upper catchment is peatland, while the lower reaches flow through farmland.
Loxogrammeae is a fern tribe with two genera that lack sclerenchyma in their plant body, except in the roots.
Phillipe J. Nover, an American MMA fighter, gained recognition for reaching the finals of The Ultimate Fighter and previously held the lightweight championship in Ring of Combat.

The Gustave Flaubert Bridge is a vertical-lift bridge over the River Seine in Rouen, France. It opened in 2008 after four years of construction and was named after the novelist Gustave Flaubert. The bridge cost €60 million, but the total cost was €137 million due to associated infrastructure.

Jason C. Ruff is a former professional ice hockey player from Kelowna, British Columbia. He was selected by the St. Louis Blues in the 1990 NHL Entry Draft and played for the Lethbridge Hurricanes before joining the NHL. Ruff played for the Belfast Giants, Ingolstadt, and Kansas City Outlaws before retiring in 2007. He then became Assistant Coach of the Lethbridge Hurricanes.

Larry Cleo Morris, a Decatur, Georgia native, was a successful American football linebacker who became an All-American at Georgia Tech and was named one of the linebackers on the NFL 1960s All-Decade Team. He is considered one of the best players the state of Georgia has produced.
Wild Child is a band from Austin, Texas, consisting of Kelsey Wilson, Alexander Beggins, Sadie Wolfe, Matt Bradshaw, and Tom Myers. They are managed by Pat Cassidy.
The Bank of Rajasthan, a private sector bank in India, merged with ICICI Bank in 2010.

April Bloomfield, a British female chef born in 1974, is famous for earning a Michelin star at The Spotted Pig and The Breslin Bar & Dining Room. She worked at various restaurants in the UK, such as The River Café and Bibendum. Additionally, she holds the record for the highest score by a single challenger in Iron Chef America history, defeating Michael Symon 56-53 in 2008.

Michito Sakaki is a Japanese-born Australian rules football player who was originally a talented university soccer player. He quickly took to Australian Football and became one of the best and most successful players to learn and play the game outside of Australia.
