He represented the Samurai, the Japanese national Australian Rules team, captaining the side in the Australian Football International Cups in both 2002 and 2005. He was later invited to train with the AFL club Essendon Football Club and became the first non-Irish international and player to learn the game overseas to play at for an AFL side. He announced his desire to play at the highest level and his intention to move to Australia to further his development.
The Yangon Central Women's Hospital is a public hospital in Myanmar that serves as a teaching hospital for several universities.
Steve Renicks, a Scottish footballer born on November 28, 1975, played for Hamilton, Stranraer, Queen of the South, and Dumbarton.

The Otoro River in Honduras starts in Intibucá and becomes the Ulúa River in Santa Barbara. The Río Gualcarque is a well-known tributary and the proposed site for the controversial Agua Zarca Dam, which gained attention after the assassination of Berta Cáceres for her opposition to the project.

Asteroid 1574 Meyer, also known as 1949 FD, is a dark, carbonaceous object located in the outer asteroid belt. It was discovered by Louis Boyer at the Algiers Observatory in 1949 and has a diameter of approximately 59 kilometers. Its orbit has an eccentricity of 0.04 and is tilted by 14 degrees to the plane of the ecliptic. It has a rotation period of 12.6 hours and a low albedo of 0.030-0.04. The asteroid is named after Georges Meyer, the director of the Algiers Observatory.

Norsk Forurensningskontroll AS was a Norwegian aviation company with four de Havilland Canada DHC-6 Twin Otter aircraft. It was founded in 1983 to apply dispersants on oil spills at sea, but failed due to politics and instead operated for charter. The company was based at Bodø Airport and cooperated with Widerøe.
Camilla d'Errico is a visual artist from Canada who works as a comic book illustrator and painter.
Adelaide of Susa, also known as Adelaide of Turin, was the final ruler of the Arduinici dynasty and held the title of Marchioness of Turin from 1034 until her passing in 1091.

George Wyllys was an early governor of the Connecticut Colony, born in Warwickshire, England to a wealthy family. He attended several universities but did not graduate. He married twice and had four children. He emigrated to New England in the early 1630s and became an Assistant to the General Court of the Massachusetts Bay Colony. He oversaw the construction of a large home in Hartford, where he later served as governor in 1642. He was also a Commissioner from Connecticut to The United Colonies of New England. He died in 1645 and is buried in Hartford's Ancient Burying Ground. Wyllys Street in Hartford is named after him.

The Verlag Theodor Steinkopff was a German publishing company in Dresden that specialized in medical and scientific books. It was founded in 1908 by Theodor Steinkopff and focused on colloid chemistry. The company had branch offices in Leipzig and Darmstadt, and Dietrich Steinkopff joined in 1927. The company became defunct in 1978, but the Darmstadt branch became an independent company and was later taken over by Springer Verlag in 1980.

Catalyst is a student magazine produced by the RMIT Student Union in Melbourne, Australia. It is published six times a year and had a readership of 58,000 in 2009. The magazine's funding comes from the university and advertising revenue, and it benefits from its proximity to the RMIT School of Media and Communication. Catalyst alumni are active in the Australian media. The magazine established a podcast called Cataclysm in 2014, which is released tri-weekly and features themed feature stories and regular segments. One of the podcast's popular segments, 'Politics on the Couch', spawned a webseries collaboration between Catalyst and RMITV called 'Politics at the Belleville'.

The AIMPE is a professional association and trade union for Australian marine and power engineers, registered with the Australian Industrial Relations Commission and affiliated with the Australian Council of Trade Unions. They represent engineers in various maritime industries and cover employed and unemployed marine engineers, officers, power plant engineers, and independent contractors who meet their criteria. Membership is expensive, but the organization is concerned with occupational health and safety and employment conditions. Despite the decline of the Australian maritime industry, the AIMPE has more members than ever due to the demand for certified engineering staff in the offshore industry. Terry Snee is the federal president.
The Supreme Court ruled in United States v. Wise (1962) that corporate officers could face penalties under the Sherman Antitrust Act while performing their duties.
Anna Rudolf, a Hungarian chess player born in 1987, holds the titles of International Master and Woman Grandmaster. She has won the Hungarian Women's Chess Championship in 2008, 2010, and 2011.

Mirza Mazhar Jan-i Janan, also known as Shamsuddin Habibullah, was a famous Naqshbandi Sufi poet from Delhi and one of the four pillars of Urdu poetry. He was known for his unwavering commitment to the Sunnah of the Islamic prophet Muhammad and established the Naqshbandi suborder Mazhariyya Shamsiyya.

Kadongo Kamu is Uganda's oldest mainstream music genre, created with only one acoustic guitar, hence the name "one little guitar" in the Ganda language. While other instruments may be used, the true style of the music relies solely on this guitar.

The 2014 FFA Cup preliminaries were state-based knockout contests that served as a qualification route for the Australian association football knockout cup competition. Most clubs entered through their state federations, competing in a state-based cup tournament to advance to the Round of 32. 22 teams will qualify from these competitions, joining the 10 A-League clubs in the Round of 32.

The Virginia Beach Sportsplex is a sports complex in Virginia Beach, Virginia, with a main stadium that opened in 1999 and has a seating capacity of 6,000, expandable to 17,000 for American football games. It was the first soccer-specific stadium built in the US and has been home to various sports teams, including the Hampton Roads Piranhas, Virginia Beach Mariners, and Virginia Beach Submariners. The stadium is now used by the Virginia Rush Organization, Norfolk Blues rugby team, and Southern Virginian Trojans semi-pro football team. In 2009, the Sportsplex was turned over to a private firm, Hometown Sports Management, who made improvements to the field and parking lot.

South Holston Lake, a 7,580-acre impoundment operated by the TVA, is located near Abingdon, Virginia and Bristol, Virginia/Tennessee. The Virginia portion of the reservoir offers anglers over 1,600 acres of water, and a South Holston Reservoir Fishing License is available for fishing the entire lake across both states.

Michał Jerzy Poniatowski was a Polish nobleman who served as Abbot of Tyniec and Czerwińsk, Bishop of Płock, Coadjutor Bishop of Kraków, Archbishop of Gniezno, and Primate of Poland. He was also a knight of the Order of the White Eagle and a Royal Member of the Royal Society.

Lauren Nourse is an Australian netball player who plays for the national team. She first gained attention in 2003 while playing for the AIS Canberra Darters and was later named in the Australian open squad in 2004. After joining the struggling Queensland Firebirds, her career turned around when Vicki Wilson took over coaching in 2006. Nourse was re-selected for the Australian squad and made her debut in 2007, performing well enough to be retained for the World Championships. She currently plays for the Queensland Firebirds in the ANZ Championship.

William Henry Gist was the Governor of South Carolina from 1858 to 1860 and played a significant role in the secession movement. He signed the Ordinance of Secession on December 20, 1860, which marked the beginning of the Confederacy.

Swiss International Air Lines is the flag carrier airline of Switzerland, operating scheduled services in Europe, North America, South America, Africa, and Asia. It was formed after the bankruptcy of Swissair in 2002 and is a member of the Star Alliance. Swiss is a subsidiary of the Lufthansa Group and has its headquarters at EuroAirport Basel-Mulhouse-Freiburg near Basel, Switzerland. The airline uses the IATA code LX and the ICAO code SWR, inherited from Swissair and Crossair, respectively.

The gillaroo is a type of trout found only in Lough Melvin in Ireland. It has a unique gene and distinctive coloring, with deep red spots and a "gizzard" used for digesting hard food. It primarily eats snails and other bottom-dwelling animals, but may come to the surface to feed in late summer. While other lakes are said to have gillaroo, the unique gene has only been found in Lough Melvin. It is not officially recognized as a separate species from brown trout. Legend has it that the gillaroo's "gizzard" came from a chicken thrown into the river by St. Brigid.
In 1995, the US Supreme Court case United States v. Alfonso D. Lopez, Jr. established boundaries for Congress' authority under the Commerce Clause, the first such ruling since the New Deal.

The Hypsiboas ornatissimus is a frog species in the Hylidae family that can be found in Brazil, Colombia, French Guiana, Guyana, Suriname, and Venezuela. It lives in subtropical or tropical moist lowland forests, freshwater marshes, and intermittent freshwater marshes.

Qanat-e Sang-e Sefid is a village in Fars Province, Iran, located in Shahidabad Rural District, Mashhad-e Morghab District, Khorrambid County. Although its existence was confirmed in the 2006 census, its population was not recorded.
The Sandy River Railroad was a narrow gauge railway constructed to serve Strong and Phillips in the Sandy River valley, making it the first narrow gauge common carrier railroad in Maine.

More! was a women's fashion magazine and website published in the UK by Bauer London Lifestyle. It covered celebrity news, high street fashion, and sex tips. It was initially published fortnightly, but became a weekly publication in September 2007 to compete with Look. More USA is still being published. However, on 22 April 2013, Bauer Media Group announced that it would stop publishing More! Magazine and its website due to challenging economic conditions.

Wolfgang Grobe, a former German football player, now works as a scout for FC Bayern Munich since June 2011. He played for nine seasons in the Bundesliga with Eintracht Braunschweig and FC Bayern Munich.

The CGT is an Anarcho-Syndicalist trade union in Spain that split from CNT/AIT in 1979. It has around 60,000 members and represents approximately 2 million workers through industrial committees and collective bargaining. The CGT is particularly strong in Catalonia and has a significant presence in the Spanish state railways and SEAT. It has been known to call for industrial action and has recently rejected a deal resulting in layoffs at SEAT. The CGT is a member of FESAL and has 5,000 labor delegates.

The Bunny the Bear's fourth album, Stories, was released in April 2013 and reached number 24 on the Billboard Top Heatseekers chart. The album features two singles, "Another Day" and "In Like Flynn," with the latter winning music video of the year on Victory Records in 2013. The album also includes a re-recorded version of "It's Not Always Cold in Buffalo," featuring altered instrumentation and vocals. A new version of the song was released in 2015 with the vocals of the band's new clean vocalist, Haley Roback.

Graeme Higginson, a former rugby union player from New Zealand, played for Canterbury and Hawke's Bay at a provincial level and was a member of the All Blacks from 1980 to 1983. He played 14 matches, including six internationals, and captained the team in one match against Australian Universities in 1980.

The First Presbyterian Church is situated at the intersection of Marsh and Morro Streets in downtown San Luis Obispo, California. It conducts Sunday services and midweek gatherings with a focus on Christian ministries of healing and reconciling.

Bernard Kincaid is a former Mayor of Birmingham, Alabama, who was elected in 1999 but lost his bid for re-election in 2007. He has a long history of political involvement, having been elected president of his fifth-grade class and later serving as president of the Miles College Student Government Association. Kincaid has also held various positions in education and community organizations, and has served on numerous boards related to his political positions. He has a Ph.D. from the University of Alabama and a J.D. from the Birmingham School of Law.

Thomas E. Gordon is the current Metropolitan Archbishop of the Orthodox Anglican Communion and the sixth Presiding Bishop of the Orthodox Anglican Church. He was nominated by Creighton Jones, his predecessor, and assumed the position on April 18, 2015. Gordon is a graduate of St. Andrew's Theological College and Seminary and is married with three sons.
The Sibiciu River is a Romanian tributary of the Buzău River.
Thomas Calloway Lea, Jr. was a well-known lawyer and former mayor of El Paso, Texas.
The JFK Medical Center in Atlantis, Florida has 460 beds and specializes in cardiovascular care. It has over 500 physicians, 2200 healthcare professionals, and 300 volunteers.
Mike Grob, an American golfer born on May 6, 1964, attended the University of Arkansas and has played on the PGA Tour, Web.com Tour, and Canadian Tour.

The Great Deceiver is a live 4CD box set by King Crimson, released in 1992 and reissued in 2007 as two volumes of 2 CDs each. The recordings feature the band's lineup from 1973 and 1974, excluding Jamie Muir who left the band in early 1973. The box set includes live recordings of the band's 1974 concert from Providence, Rhode Island, and reproduces the band's "walk-on" music from that era. Some recordings from the box set were previously available on other King Crimson albums. The liner notes include comments from band members, excerpts from Fripp's diary, and a complete listing of all concerts performed by the band in 1973 and 1974. The song "Exiles" is credited incorrectly on the box set.

Bob Lagomarsino, a former Republican congressman from California, served in the United States House of Representatives from 1974 to 1992, when he was defeated for renomination by Michael Huffington. Before that, he served in the California State Senate from 1961 to 1974 and was the mayor of Ojai, California.

Petite, also known as Vincent Aycocho, is a Filipino actor, comedian, singer, and TV show host. He is famous for his comedic performances in Comedy Bar, Paunch line, and clowns, alongside other celebrities such as Boobay, Iyah, Donita Nose, Ate Gay, Allan K., and Wally Bayola. Petite has numerous projects in GMA Network, including hosting CelebriTV with Joey de Leon and being Lolit's partner.

Miguel Paz Baraona was President of Honduras from 1925 to 1929, nominated by the National Party of Honduras. He won the election with 99% of the vote as the Liberal Party of Honduras refused to nominate a candidate. His presidency brought stability to Honduras for three decades and he has an elementary school named after him.

Jack Parr was an American basketball player born in Louisville, Kentucky. He played college basketball at Kansas State University and was drafted by the Cincinnati Royals in the 10th round of the 1958 NBA draft. Parr played 66 games for the Royals in 1958–1959, averaging 4.0 points per game. He was known for his intensity and inner drive, and his defensive play against Wilt Chamberlain in 1958 helped K-State win a thrilling 79-75 victory. Parr received All-America recognition twice and still holds KSU's single-season rebounding record. He died in January 2015 at the age of 78.
Andy Fenton, an Irish ex-athlete born in 1952, played hurling for Kiltormer and was part of the Galway senior inter-county team during the 1970s.

The sooty-capped bush tanager is a small bird found in the highlands of Costa Rica and western Panama. It builds a bulky cup nest and lays two pink-brown eggs marked with white. The adult bird has a blackish head with a white supercilium and a grey throat, and feeds on insects, spiders, and small fruits. It is easily distinguished from the common bush tanager by its blacker head and obvious supercilium.

Aonghus Clarke is an Irish hurler from Castletown Geoghegan, County Westmeath. He plays as a left corner-forward for the Westmeath senior team and made his debut in 2012. He previously played for the Westmeath minor and under-21 teams. Clarke has won a championship medal with his club, Castletown Geoghegan, and his brother, Joe, also plays for Westmeath.

Dan Flood was a Democratic US Representative from Pennsylvania who served from 1955 to 1980. He helped the Wilkes-Barre area recover after the 1972 Agnes Flood, but was censured for bribery in 1980 and resigned from the House.
Saint Ansgar, also called Anskar or Saint Anschar, was a German Archbishop of Hamburg-Bremen who was known as the "Apostle of the North" for his mission to bring Christianity to Northern Europe.

Robert William Harrison, a retired American professional basketball player, played for nine seasons in the NBA and averaged 7.2 points per game. He also appeared in the 1956 NBA All-Star Game and later coached at Kenyon College and Harvard University. As a 13-year-old, he scored all 139 points in a game for his school team.

Samvel Mnatsyan, a Russian ice hockey defenceman born on March 5, 1990, is currently playing for Admiral Vladivostok in the KHL. He also played for HC Kladno in the Czech Extraliga during the 2010-11 season.

Podagrica malvae is a leaf beetle found in Southern and Central Europe, the East Palearctic ecozone, the Near East, and North Africa. It feeds on different Malvaceae species and has dark blue elytra and reddish pronotum, head, and legs. The adults are 3-4 millimeters long.

OSU Medical Center in Tulsa, Oklahoma is a teaching hospital with medical clinics and numerous osteopathic residency and fellowship programs. It is accredited by the American Osteopathic Association and receives around 45,000 emergency room visits annually. The hospital is set to receive $40 million in funding for technology and facility improvements, including an expansion of the intensive care unit and renovations to women's health and neonatal intensive care unit programs. It is the largest osteopathic teaching center in the US, training 126 resident physicians each year.
The 1955 Washington Redskins aimed to do better than their 3-9 record in the previous year.

The Touvedo Dam is a concrete gravity dam on the Limia in Ponte da Barca, Portugal. It was constructed between 1987 and 1993 and is owned by CPPE. The dam serves the purposes of power generation, irrigation, and flood control.

Bernard de Castanet, a bishop and cardinal of the Catholic Church, served as the Inquisitor of Languedoc and Vice-Inquisitor of France, despite not being a member of the Dominican order. He maintained a positive relationship with the Preachers.

Lee Emmett Thomas was a lawyer and banker who held the position of mayor of Shreveport, Louisiana from 1922 to 1930, and was also the Speaker of the Louisiana House of Representatives from 1912 to 1916.

BK Liepājas Lauvas is a Latvian professional basketball club that competes in the Latvian and Baltic Basketball Leagues. The team has had several names in the past, but since 2012 it has been known as Liepāja/Triobet. Their best performance in the Latvian Basketball League was a second-place finish in 1997, while they finished third in 2000, 2011, and 2012.

Dagsavisen, a daily newspaper in Oslo, Norway, was previously affiliated with the Norwegian Labour Party but became independent from 1975 to 1999. It is now partially owned by Christian groups and has had various names, including Arbeiderbladet from 1923 to 1997.

The Roman Catholic Diocese of Annecy is a French diocese of the Latin Rite of the Roman Catholic church. It was established in 1822 as a subdivision of the Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Chambéry and covers the department of Haute-Savoie. In 2002, it became a suffragan to the Archdiocese of Lyon and is currently led by Archbishop Yves Jean Marie Arsène Boivineau, appointed in 2001.
SR 568 is a brief extension of SR 589, built in 1994 and renamed in 2001. It links SR 589 to SR 597 and is part of the Veterans Expressway, which was meant to extend to Lutz, Florida.
Elizabeth Fraser, an ex-Australian swimmer, participated in the women's 4 × 100 metre freestyle relay during the 1956 Summer Olympics.

Mount Meru is a dormant stratovolcano in Tanzania, located 70 km west of Mount Kilimanjaro. It is the fifth highest mountain in Africa and lost much of its bulk 8,000 years ago due to a volcanic blast. It had a minor eruption in 1910 and has several small cones and craters. Mount Meru is the centerpiece of Arusha National Park and supports a forest with diverse wildlife, including nearly 400 bird species, monkeys, and leopards.

i-D is a UK magazine that focuses on fashion, music, art, and youth culture. It was created by Terry Jones, a designer and former Vogue art director, in 1980. The magazine started as a hand-stapled fanzine with typewriter text and has since become a glossy publication while still maintaining its focus on street style and youth culture. i-D has also organized exhibitions globally and released multiple books.

Amanda J. Dobbs is an American figure skater who placed fourth at the 2010 Four Continents Championships as a single skater and also competed in pair skating with Joseph Jacobsen at the national senior level.
Walter Eucken, a German economist from the Freiburg school, is known as the father of ordoliberalism and is associated with the creation of the idea of a "social market economy."

Sade, an English band formed in 1982, has released six studio albums, two compilation albums, two live albums, two EPs, 23 singles, five video albums, and 20 music videos. Sade Adu, the lead singer, began as a backup singer for a band named Pride before forming Sade. Their debut album, Diamond Life, sold over six million copies and became one of the top-selling debut recordings of the '80s. The band went on to release several multi-platinum selling albums, including Promise, Love Deluxe, and Lovers Rock. After a ten-year hiatus, they returned with their sixth album, Soldier of Love, which won a Grammy award.

RMIT University is a public research university in Melbourne, Australia, founded in 1887 as a night school for art, science, and technology. It has grown from 320 students to around 83,000 vocational, undergraduate, and postgraduate students as of 2015. It has campuses in Melbourne, Vietnam, and Spain, and is ranked as the top art and design school in Australia and the Southern Hemisphere.

The National Revolutionary Party was founded in Afghanistan in 1974 by President Mohammed Daoud Khan to gain support for his republican regime and undermine the communists who helped him come to power. The party banned all other political parties and was run by a central committee. However, it did not survive the Saur Revolution in April 1978.

The Icelandic entry in the 1992 Eurovision Song Contest was a duet called "No Or Yes?" by Heart 2 Heart, expressing uncertainty about a relationship but hoping for the best. It placed 7th out of 23 entries and was succeeded the following year by Inga with "Then You Know the Answer."

Break The Barrier was a wrestling event held in Philadelphia in 1999, organized by Scoopswrestling.com founders. It featured wrestlers from 12 independent promotions and was called one of the greatest Supercards of all time by Pro Wrestling Illustrated. Tom Brandi won the main event but attacked the promoter instead of accepting the trophy. Abdullah the Butcher attacked two wrestlers in a "First blood" match. Three new champions were crowned, and Shane Douglas delivered a controversial interview before quitting ECW.

Overwatch is a team-based first-person shooter video game developed and published by Blizzard Entertainment. Players select from a variety of hero characters with unique attributes and skills, divided into four classes, and work together to secure control points or escort a payload across a map. The game offers cosmetic rewards and free updates, with microtransactions available for additional cosmetic items. Overwatch was created by a portion of the team behind the canceled Titan project, and features a diverse cast of heroes set in an optimistic near-future Earth. The game was well-received upon release, praised for its accessibility and enjoyable gameplay.
The Rochester Jr. Americans, a Tier III Junior A ice hockey team from Rochester, New York, had a top team that played in both the Premier and Elite Divisions of the USPHL.

Aquarius Records is an independent record label founded in Montreal in 1969. Its first president was Terry Flood and its other founding owners were Donald Tarlton, Bob Lemm, Dan Lazare, and Jack Lazare. The label was originally distributed by London Records of Canada and signed acts such as April Wine, Walter Rossi, and Teaze. In 1978, Aquarius changed distribution to Capitol-EMI and signed Corey Hart, Sass Jordan, and Mindstorm. The label sold over 5 million records in Canada and launched a French-language label called Tacca Musique in the 1990s. Aquarius was entirely acquired by Donald Tarlton by the end of the 1990s and expanded through new imprints and joint ventures. Its biggest selling new artist was Sum 41, and it also had distribution deals with Unidisc Music.

BBVA Compass Stadium in Houston, Texas is a soccer-specific stadium that is home to the Houston Dynamo, Houston Dash, and Texas Southern Tigers football. The stadium was built with a combined commitment of $95.5 million from the city of Houston, Houston Dynamo, and Harris County. It is located in East Downtown and is sponsored by BBVA Compass.

Yukio Endo was a Japanese gymnast who won gold medals in the team event at the 1960 Olympics and 1962 World Championships. He also won the first individual all-around Olympic gold medal for Japan in 1964 and was the flag bearer at the 1968 Olympics.

Robinsons Place Dumaguete is a large shopping mall in Dumaguete City, Negros Oriental, with a gross floor area of over 45,000 square meters and located on almost 60,000 square meters of land area. It is the first full-service largest shopping mall in Negros Oriental and is a major component of the Dumaguete Business Park and IT Plaza in Brgy. Calindagan. The mall features an activity center, two atria, and an al fresco dining area. It opened on November 23, 2009, and is the 27th shopping mall development of Robinsons Malls. The mall has been awarded by the Philippine Retailers Association (PRA) as the Mall of the Year for 2012.

Bruce Bruce, originally named Bruce Church, is an American comedian and actor hailing from Atlanta, Georgia. He was raised in The Bluff, a tough neighborhood in the city, and has hosted BET's ComicView and appeared in numerous comedy specials and TV shows. Additionally, he served as a spokesperson for Popeye's Chicken & Biscuits.

ARMA Tactics THD is a mobile simulation game developed by Bohemia Interactive for iOS and Android devices. It was released in May 2013 for the Nvidia Shield and is a turn-based tactical game where the player controls a squad of operatives.
The Toronto Argonauts of 1948 came in third in the Interprovincial Rugby Football Union, with a record of 5-6-1, and did not qualify for the playoffs.
Ivan Aleksandrovich Minin, born on January 22, 1988, is a retired Russian footballer.

Maryland Route 404 is a major highway on the Eastern Shore of Maryland that runs from Wye Mills to the Delaware state line. It connects cities west of the Chesapeake Bay to the Delaware Beaches and passes through farmland and woodland as well as the towns of Queen Anne, Hillsboro, and Denton. The road is mostly two-lane undivided with exceptions near Denton and Hillsboro. The route has been realigned several times since its designation in 1933 and has a high accident rate. The Maryland State Highway Administration plans to widen the two-lane portions of the route into a four-lane divided highway.

Ilija Grgic is a former Australian rules footballer who played for Footscray, West Coast Eagles, and Essendon in the 1990s. He made nine appearances in his debut season, receiving a nomination for the 1993 AFL Rising Star award. In 1994, he was Footscray's number one ruckman and received nine Brownlow Medal votes. He was traded to West Coast in 1996 and played as their regular ruckman in 1997. He suffered back problems in 1998 and played most of his football for Peel Thunder in the WAFL. He was picked up by Essendon in the 1998 AFL Draft but could only manage two AFL appearances due to injury. After retiring from football, he had a successful career in the oil and gas industry.

Ctesylla was a maiden from Ioulis in Ceos who was seen dancing by an Athenian named Hermochares during the Pythian festival. He threw an apple with an oath carved on it, which obliged her to marry him. Her father agreed, but then forgot his oath and planned to give her to another man. Ctesylla fell in love with Hermochares and they ran off to Athens to get married. However, Ctesylla died in labour as retribution for her father breaking his oath. Hermochares founded a sanctuary dedicated to Ctesylla, and sacrifices were offered to Aphrodite Ctesylla in Ioulis.
Psilocybe semiangustipleurocystidiata is a type of psilocybin mushroom that was discovered in 2004 in Colombia. It grows in tropical forests on clay soil.

Little Fish is a musical based on two short stories by Deborah Eisenberg, about a group of friends in New York City. One character, Charlotte, quits smoking and takes up swimming. The creator, Michael John LaChiusa, views the musical as a parable for New York after 9/11.

The Sarasvati Pushkaram festival, which happens every 12 years, celebrates the invisible Saraswati River that flows at Triveni Sangam. It lasts for 12 days, starting when Jupiter enters Mithuna rasi (Gemini).

Canadian short track speed skater Liam McFarlane, born in Medicine Hat, Alberta on December 30, 1985, was a member of the gold medal-winning relay team at the 2012 World Short Track Speed Skating Championships.
Dóra Turóczi, a Hungarian ice dancer born in Budapest on December 1, 1990, is the 2011 Hungarian bronze medalist with her partner Balázs Major. They primarily train in Budapest.
Jessie DeZiel, an American artistic gymnast born on August 12, 1993, was part of the University of Nebraska gymnastics team from 2012 to 2015 while studying there.

EMMC is home to Lifeflight of Maine and is a key training affiliate of the University of New England College of Osteopathic Medicine. Leapfrog Group rated EMMC as one of 16 "A"-rated hospitals for safety in Maine, with 80% of the state's hospitals receiving "A" grades, second only to Massachusetts with 83%.

Formed in 2002, Faun is a German band that plays pagan folk, darkwave, and medieval music. They use traditional instruments and sing in various languages, including German, Latin, Greek, and Scandinavian languages. Their instruments include the Celtic harp, Swedish nyckelharpa, hurdy-gurdy, bagpipes, cittern, flutes, and more.
François Simons, a retired Belgian swimmer born on October 25, 1946, participated in the 1964 and 1968 Summer Olympics in the 100m and 200m freestyle events but did not make it to the finals.

Lake Buel is a 196-acre pond in Berkshire County, Massachusetts surrounded by summer and year-round homes in separate neighborhoods with private or semi-private roads. It is named after Samuel C. Buel who saved people from drowning on the lake in 1812. The lake has a boat ramp and a portion of the Appalachian Trail crosses over a breached mill dam along the northern inlet.

The Bruchsal Rollenberg junction is a complex intersection of high-speed railways in Baden-Württemberg, Germany. The Ubstadt connecting curve branches off from Heidelberg in the northwest, while the Bruchsal connecting curve branches off from Bruchsal and Karlsruhe in the southwest.

John James Boys was an English cricketer who played first-class cricket in the mid 1870s and early 1880s. He was a right-handed batsman and wicket-keeper who played for the Royal Artillery and Kent. He scored 34 runs and made four catches and two stumpings in his four matches. He died suddenly in 1883 on the day of his planned wedding.

The Siderurgistul Stadium in Galaţi, Romania was constructed in the early 2000s and is primarily used for football games, serving as the home field for Oţelul Galaţi. It has a capacity of approximately 6,000 spectators.

The Cincinnati-Newport Bridge, a cantilever bridge connecting Newport, Kentucky and Cincinnati, Ohio, was built in 1890 and demolished in 1992 to make room for the Taylor-Southgate Bridge. Some of the decorative ironwork was moved to the new bridge.
The longhorn beetle species Anisopodus acutus was identified by Thomson in 1865 and is found in Brazil.
Rob Modra is an Australian professional darts player in the PDC.

Lt Col Shanti Swaroop Rana was a brave Indian military officer who destroyed four terrorist hideouts in Jammu & Kashmir. He killed two foreign mercenaries and charged towards another terrorist, ultimately sacrificing his own life. For his bravery, he was posthumously awarded the Ashoka Chakra.

MedChemComm is a monthly peer-reviewed scientific journal that publishes original research and review articles on medicinal chemistry, drug discovery, pharmacology, and pharmaceutical chemistry. It is the official journal of the European Federation for Medicinal Chemistry and is published by the Royal Society of Chemistry. The journal offers open access publishing options and has an impact factor of 2.495 according to the Journal Citation Reports. The editors-in-chief are Anthony Wood and Greg Verdine.

Harvey Alfred Branch was a left-handed pitcher who played in the minor leagues for seven years and had only one game in the Major League with the St. Louis Cardinals. He attended Alabama State University and was originally signed with the Chicago Cubs. In 1962, he was traded to the Cardinals and made his MLB appearance against the Cubs, yielding three runs in five innings. He left the game with St. Louis trailing and was the losing pitcher. Branch made the Cardinals' 40-man spring training roster in 1963 but was sent to the Triple-A Atlanta Crackers for the full season. He left the game after spending 1964 in the minor leagues.

Alan McCullough Jr. was a modernist architect from Norfolk, Virginia who gained popularity after World War II for his Virginia residences. He combined modern design with local elements and was influenced by Frank Lloyd Wright. His trademark features included terrazzo floors and raised fireplaces with levitating hearths. He designed notable schools and buildings for companies such as C&P Telephone, United Virginia Bank, and The Tides Inn. McCullough retired in 1972 and died at age 84 in a Richmond hospital.
Bema ydda is a type of snout moth belonging to the Bema genus. It was identified by Dyar in 1914 and is found in Panama.

KJNP-TV is a TBN-affiliated television station in North Pole, Alaska that also serves Fairbanks. It was founded by Don and Gen Nelson and became a TBN affiliate in 1990. KJNP-TV broadcasts Closing Comments and is the only television station in the US broadcasting from a place called the "North Pole." The previous North Pole, New York-based station, WPTZ, moved its city of license to Plattsburgh in 2011.

The Dutch rock band Claw Boys Claw released a compilation album called 3 in 1, also known as Claw Boys Claw. It includes songs from their Indian Wallpaper, So Mean, and Now! singles. The album was released on LP by Polydor.

Air Dream, a charter airline based in Cambodia, operated flights between Siem Reap and Hanoi in 2007. The airline, which had only one aircraft chartered from Royal Khmer Airlines, was shut down and its plane was left at Noi Bai International Airport in Hanoi for maintenance reasons.

TEN 2 is a 24-hour sports channel in South Asia owned by Zee Entertainment Enterprises. It was previously known as Zee Sports and TEN Action+. The channel broadcasts various sports events including UEFA Champions League, I-League, and the Durand Cup. It also features a show called C2K hosted by Andrew Leci and other football legends.

Bokang Montjane, a South African model and beauty pageant winner, was crowned Miss South Africa 2010 and represented her country in Miss Universe 2011 and Miss World 2011. She also participated in Miss International 2009 and was named Miss World Africa in 2011.

The Roman Catholic Diocese of Ratnapura is a Latin Rite diocese in Sri Lanka, established in 1995 from the Diocese of Galle. It is under the jurisdiction of the Archdiocese of Colombo and led by Bishop Cletus Chandrasiri Perera since 2007.

The Etmopterus lucifer, also known as the blackbelly lanternshark or lucifer shark, is a type of shark from the Etmopteridae family. It can be found in tropical to temperate seas worldwide, at depths ranging from 150 to 1,250 meters. This shark can grow up to 47 centimeters in length and is ovoviviparous.
Chinatsu Matsui is a Japanese professional squash player with a highest world ranking of 50 in September 2007.

Mis-Teeq, a British girl group, released three studio albums, one compilation album, eight singles, one video album and one promotional single. The group was formed in 1999 with Alesha Dixon, Sabrina Washington and Su-Elise Nash, but Zena McNally left after their debut single. In February 2005, the group announced their split to pursue solo careers.

David Britton Funderburk was the US Ambassador to Romania from 1981 to 1985 and a Republican US Representative from North Carolina from 1995 to 1997. He was born in Virginia, grew up in North Carolina, and earned degrees from Wake Forest University and the University of South Carolina. Before entering politics, he worked as a history professor and received several honors, including Romania's highest award to a foreigner. Funderburk wrote a book about his time in Romania and ran for the US Senate in 1986 but was defeated. He was elected to the 104th Congress in 1994 but lost his bid for reelection to the 105th Congress. He currently lives in North Carolina.
Susanna Agnelli was an Italian politician, businesswoman, and writer who became the first woman to hold the position of Minister of Foreign Affairs in Italy.

Mount Hook is a snow-covered mountain located on the east side of Saratoga Table, 5 nautical miles southeast of Sorna Bluff in the Forrestal Range of the Pensacola Mountains, Antarctica. It was named after Lieutenant Commander Richard M. Hook of the U.S. Navy, who served as a Medical Officer at South Pole Station in the winter of 1968.
Cheshmeh Sard is a village in Iran's Lorestan Province with a population of 141 people in 28 families according to the 2006 census.

Petrus Peckius the Elder was a prominent Dutch jurist who wrote about international maritime law and remained loyal to the Crown during the Eighty Years' War. He was appointed a justice in the Great Council in 1582 and was married to Catharina Gillis with whom he had children.

The Aldrich Coal Mine Museum is a historical museum in Montevallo, Alabama, located in the former company store of the town. It contains artifacts and displays from Aldrich's coal mine, churches, school, prison, stores, and post office, as well as the only coal miner monument in Alabama. The museum is housed in the former Montevallo Mine Company commissary, which is listed on the Alabama Register of Landmarks and Heritage.
The Leucosiidae family includes the Leucisca crab genus, which is found only in South Africa.

"Bongo Bong" is Manu Chao's first solo single from his album Clandestino, and is a remake of his own band Mano Negra's song "King of Bongo" from 1991. The song also uses background music from Black Uhuru's "Bull ina di Pen" and is part of a medley with "Je ne t'aime plus" on the album. The music has been reused for other songs and has been covered by Robbie Williams and remixed by various artists.

Fiona pinnata is a unique species of small sea slug that lives on floating objects in oceans worldwide. It feeds mainly on goose barnacles and has unusual anatomy, including features unique to its monotypic family, Fionidae. These features include identical oral tentacles and rhinophores, cerata with a membrane and no cnidosac, a dorsally directed anus, two genital openings, two jaws with a cutting-edge, and a radula with a single central denticle and surrounding cusps.

Since the IRA ceasefire in 1997, dissident Irish republicans have continued a low-level armed campaign against British security forces in Northern Ireland. The main groups involved are the Real IRA, Continuity IRA, and Óglaigh na hÉireann. They have targeted the British Army and PSNI with guns, bombs, mortars, and rockets, as well as carrying out disruptive bombings. The campaign has not been as intense as the Provisional IRA's, and since the end of Operation Banner in 2007, the PSNI has been the main target. The dissident campaign began towards the end of the Troubles, a 30-year period of conflict resulting in over 3,500 deaths. Two British soldiers, two PSNI officers, and two Prison Service guards have been killed as part of the republican campaign, and at least 105 civilians have been killed by republican and loyalist paramilitaries.
The Turkish State Hydraulic Works supported the construction of Kestel Dam in Turkey.

Contumyces is a brightly colored bryophilous agaric genus found in the Northern Hemisphere, inhabiting mossy silty or sandy soils. It has an omphalinoid morphology and was previously classified in Omphalina. Phylogenetically related agarics include Rickenella, Gyroflexus, Loreleia, Cantharellopsis, Blasiphalia, Muscinupta, Cotylidia, and Alloclavaria. Contumyces is most similar to Rickenella and Blasiphalia but differs in having clustered cystidia on the cap, stipe, and hymenium, while Rickenella and Blasiphalia have solitary cystidia.

The mimic shiner is a type of fish in the Notropis genus, found in various areas including the Hudson Bay and Great Lakes drainage, Mississippi River basin, and Gulf of Mexico. It is difficult to identify in the wild due to its resemblance to other shiners, and may actually be a group of cryptic species. Its diet consists of insects, crustaceans, and midge pupae and larvae. Mimic shiners live for three years and spawn in large schools over aquatic plants in lakes, or in clear pools over gravel substrate in small streams. They are suspected to have been introduced to many areas via bait bucket release, but conservation efforts are not currently necessary as negative impacts have not been documented and the species is not threatened.

Vladimir Grigoryevich Shukhov was a Russian engineer, scientist, and architect who made significant contributions to structural engineering and industrial design. He invented the first cracking method and developed new methods of analysis for various structures, including hyperboloid structures, diagrid shell structures, tensile structures, gridshell structures, oil reservoirs, pipelines, boilers, ships, and barges. Shukhov also created a new family of doubly curved structural forms based on non-Euclidean hyperbolic geometry, known as hyperboloids of revolution. He is renowned for his original designs of hyperboloid towers, such as the Shukhov Tower.

ISFIN is a global network of professional firms that specialize in Islamic Finance, investments in and from the Muslim world, and the Halal industry. It was established in 2011 by Laurent Marlière and is based in Brussels.

Sarojini Devi Eye Hospital is a teaching hospital in Hyderabad, India, affiliated with Osmania Medical College and Gandhi Medical College. It specializes in eye treatment and has a 550-bed capacity. The hospital is known for treating poor and underprivileged patients for free. It has five sub-specialties and nine clinical units, with state-of-the-art equipment and technology. The hospital made headlines in 1980 when a 2-year-old girl had her healthy eye removed instead of the cancerous one, resulting in the Indian government sending her to the US for treatment. The hospital was founded on the birthday of Sarojini Naidu, after whom it is named.

Lake Vidraru is a man-made reservoir in Romania created in 1965 by the Vidraru Dam on the Argeș River. It has a water volume of 465 million cubic meters, a length of 10.3 km, and a width of 2.2 km. The lake is situated in the shadow of the Făgăraș Mountains and has an installed capacity of 220 MW. It is also a popular spot for bungee jumping and leisure boat racing. The Vidraru Dam construction took five and a half years and required the excavation of 42 km of underground tunnels, 1.768 million m3 of rock, and the installation of 6300 tonnes of electromechanical equipment.

Dorie S. Murrey is a retired American basketball player who played in the NBA from 1966 to 1972. He played for the Detroit Pistons, Seattle SuperSonics, Portland Trail Blazers, and Baltimore Bullets. He averaged 4.7 points and 4.4 rebounds per game in 357 career games.

Kimilsungia is a type of orchid that was created by orchid breeder C.L. Bundt in Indonesia in 1964 and named after his daughter. It has a complex ancestry from cultivated orchids and is a clone of a plant. The correct cultivar name is Dendrobium Clara Bundt 'Kimilsungia'. It is not the national flower of North Korea, which is the Magnolia sieboldii with white flowers. The Kimilsungia orchid is used in state-sponsored propaganda surrounding the late leader Kim Il-sung.
The calafate rust, or Aecidium magellanicum, is a type of rust fungi that can cause witches broom growth on Berberis buxifolia shrubs in Argentina and Chile.
The UNSW-Eastern Suburbs Bulldogs is a Sydney AFL Premier League football club located in the eastern suburbs of Sydney, New South Wales, and is associated with the University of New South Wales.

The Big Four Bridge is a former railroad truss bridge that spans the Ohio River, connecting Louisville, Kentucky, and Jeffersonville, Indiana. It was converted into a pedestrian and bicycle bridge in 2013, with a pedestrian ramp on the Kentucky side and a ramp on the Jeffersonville side opening in 2014. The project was funded by Kentucky, Indiana, and the City of Jeffersonville.

The 1976 British Grand Prix was held at Brands Hatch in Kent, UK. James Hunt crashed at the first corner and drove his damaged car back to the pits, but did not complete a full lap of the track. Officials initially declared that Hunt would not be allowed to take part in the restart, causing anger among the British crowd. However, Hunt was eventually allowed to restart and won the race. After the race, three teams protested against the inclusion of Hunt's car, and two months later, Hunt was disqualified, giving Niki Lauda the win.

"Let's Get Together" is a song from the 1961 Disney film, The Parent Trap, written by Robert and Richard Sherman. It was sung by Hayley Mills as a duet with herself, as she played twin sisters. The song became a top 10 hit and led to Mills recording an album. The song has been covered by various artists, including Annette Funicello, Lindsay Lohan, and The Go-Go's."

KS Tomex Cracovia is a women's handball team from Kraków, Poland, and a part of the sports club KS Cracovia. The team had a successful period between 1957 and 1961, winning four national championships and reaching the semifinals of the European Cup in 1968. They won four more titles in the 1980s but have since declined and currently play in the third tier.

Urbana is a Christian student missions conference sponsored by InterVarsity Christian Fellowship that lasts for 5 days at the end of December. It aims to inform Christian students about global issues and encourage them to participate in cross-cultural missions. The conference includes dozens of seminars, diverse worship styles, and a final communion on New Year's Eve. It was first held in 1946 in Toronto and has generally been held every three years. The most recent conference was held in December 2015.
Loikaw Township is located in the eastern part of Kayah State in Myanmar and is part of Loikaw District. The main town is Loikaw.

Pat Kelly, a former Mayo inter county footballer, currently plays for St Vincents. He won the Dublin Senior Football Championship in 2007 and the Leinster Senior Club Football Championship final against Tyrrellspass. In 2008, he also won the All-Ireland Senior Club Football Championship with St Vincents in a tough match.

The 1985 Brazilian Grand Prix was the opening race of the 1985 FIA Formula One World Championship held on April 7, 1985 at Jacarepaguá. René Arnoux was fired by Ferrari after finishing 4th, and Stefan Johansson was signed by the team after finishing 7th. Nigel Mansell began his seven-season stint with Williams at this race.

Hsuan Hua was a Chan Buddhist monk who played a significant role in introducing Chinese Buddhism to the US. He established several institutions, including the Dharma Realm Buddhist Association, the City of Ten Thousand Buddhas, and Dharma Realm Buddhist University. The Buddhist Text Translation Society, which translates Buddhist scriptures into various languages, was also founded by him.

The 27th annual Survivor Series, a WWE professional wrestling pay-per-view event, took place on November 24, 2013 at the TD Garden in Boston. It was the 11th pay-per-view in the 2013 lineup and had weak sales due to poor promotion. The main event saw Randy Orton retain the WWE Championship by defeating Big Show, while John Cena retained the World Heavyweight Championship by defeating Alberto Del Rio and CM Punk and Daniel Bryan defeated The Wyatt Family's Luke Harper and Erick Rowan in other prominent matches.
Pierre Bostani, also known as Boutros Boustani, held various positions within the Catholic Church, including Archbishop and Bishop, and was a Council Father of the First Vatican Council.

John Divilly, a former Galway footballer, won the All-Ireland in 1998 and was featured in the documentary A Year Til Sunday. He currently manages the NUIM Sigerson Cup team, which won against UUJ in February 2010.

The Toei Ōedo Line is a Tokyo subway operated by Toei, which began full operations on December 12, 2000. It is completely underground and the second-longest railway tunnel in Japan. The line is represented by the color magenta and stations are labeled with the letter "E" followed by a two-digit number.
Howard Brenton's early play, Christie in Love, depicts the life of John Christie, a serial killer who killed at least six women between 1943 and 1953, and was eventually caught, tried, and executed.
The Senate is the higher chamber of Equatorial Guinea's Parliament.

Jason Kenny is an English track cyclist who specializes in individual and team sprints. He has won multiple World and European Junior titles and has achieved medals in the under 23 European championships. Kenny won a gold medal in the team sprint at the 2008 Summer Olympics in Beijing and a silver medal in the individual sprint. He has won six Olympic gold medals, placing him joint 27th in terms of gold medals won in the modern Summer Olympic games.
Jon Akass, a Fleet Street journalist, was born on July 16, 1933 and died on June 4, 1990.

The Misis Mosaic Museum displays mosaics from a 4th-century temple in the ancient city of Misis, excavated from the Misis Tumulus. The museum is located in Yakapınar village and showcases various periods in chronological order, including floor mosaics from a Basilica within the Misis Ancient City. The museum was founded in 1959 and has been enriched with works transferred from the Adana Archeological Museum and dispersed architectural elements found around Misis.
From 1954 to 1956, the Kitchener Canucks were a junior ice hockey team in the Ontario Hockey Association, playing home games at the Kitchener Memorial Auditorium in Kitchener, Ontario, Canada.

The asteroid 1694 Kaiser, also known as 1934 SB, is a carbonaceous asteroid with an eccentric orbit and a diameter of approximately 16 kilometers. It was discovered by Hendrik van Gent in 1934 and has a period of 3.71 years. Its geometric albedo is high, with varying measurements, and it has a light-curve period of 13.02-13.23 hours. It was named after Dutch astronomer Frederik Kaiser and was originally mistakenly named Kapteyn.

Dennis Jones was an Australian rules footballer who played and coached Melbourne in the VFL. He was a half-back and won the 1959 premiership. Jones retired at 25 and later coached Central District in the SANFL and West Perth in the WAFL. He returned to Melbourne as coach in 1978 but the team finished last.

Aurigny Air Services is the flag carrier airline of the Bailiwick of Guernsey, owned by the States of Guernsey since 2003. It operates passenger and freight services between the Channel Islands, northern France, and the UK, with its main base at Guernsey Airport. The airline is one of the oldest established airlines in Britain and is named after Alderney.

Phineas and Ferb: The Video Game is an action platform game based on the animated TV series of the same name. It was released for the Nintendo DS in North America on February 3, 2009, and in the UK on March 23. The game follows the show's plot, with players controlling Phineas and Ferb as they embark on summer adventures and try to avoid their sister Candace. Mini games are included, and Perry the Platypus has his own mini game where he fights Dr. Doofenshmirtz. The game's controls are simple, and the final segment involves a roller coaster race. The game was not created by the show's creators.
The Borneo python, also known as the Bornean short python or Borneo short-tailed python, is a non-venomous species found only on the island of Borneo.

Francis Ryley Heakes was a Canadian architect who studied under Kivas Tully in the mid-1880s and served as Chief Architect of the Public Works Department of the Province of Ontario. He supervised the execution of various provincial buildings from 1896 until 1926, including the Whitney Block, the Mining Building at the University of Toronto, and the Superior Court of Justice in Thunder Bay. He also designed Government House in Toronto (Chorley Park), which was one of the most expensive residences ever constructed in Canada at the time and was demolished in 1961.
Sean De Bie, son of former cyclist Eddy De Bie and nephew of former cyclist Danny De Bie, is a Belgian cyclist for Lotto-Soudal and was included in the 2016 Giro d'Italia start list.

The 2015 Pacific Games men's football tournament was held in Port Moresby, Papua New Guinea from 3-17 July 2015. It was restricted to men's under-23 national teams and also served as the 7th edition of the OFC Men's Olympic Qualifying Tournament. The tournament was combined with a separate qualifying tournament due to the participation of the New Zealand team. There were two knockout stages, one for Olympic qualifying and another for determining the Pacific Games medalists. New Caledonia won the Pacific Games gold medal, while Fiji qualified for the Olympic football tournament for the first time.

The North Dakota State Bison football team, led by coach Craig Bohl, had a successful 2010 season, finishing 9-5 and receiving an at-large qualifier bid into the FCS playoffs. Despite not being expected to make the playoffs, they won their first two games before losing in the Quarterfinals due to a controversial fumble call. This playoff run was a surprise for fans and alumni who had not experienced playoff victory in over a decade.

Shane Fell is a former Australian rules footballer who played for Sydney in the AFL. He was recruited from Glenorchy and was the TFL Statewide League's leading goal-kicker in 1989. Fell made his debut in the opening round of the 1990 AFL season and kicked five goals to equal the club record. He finished the year with 30 goals, including a six-goal haul against Geelong at the SCG.
Tuffy Leemans was an American football player who played for the New York Giants in the NFL from 1936 to 1943 and was inducted into the Pro Football Hall of Fame in 1978.

Vyacheslav Alexandrovich Alexandrov was a squad commander in the 9th airborne company, 345th Independent Guards Airborne Regiment, 40th Army. He used a heavy machine gun to repel a mujahideen attack during the Battle for Hill 3234, allowing his fellow paratroopers to move to better defensive positions. He was killed in action and posthumously awarded the title of Hero of the Soviet Union.

The Winnipeg Blue Bombers had a successful 2011 season, finishing in 1st place in the East division with a 10-8 record and clinching their first playoff berth since 2008. They advanced to the 99th Grey Cup but lost to the BC Lions, extending their drought to 21 years without a championship. The team also set a franchise record for season tickets sold with over 21,000.
The spider species Avicularia alticeps is exclusive to Uruguay in South America and is classified under the tarantula family Theraphosidae.

Gradhiva is a journal founded in 1986 by Michel Leiris and Jean Jamin, and since 2005 published by the Musée du Quai Branly in Paris. Its title is derived from a novel by W. Jensen and was edited at the Musée de l'Homme in Paris. The journal initially focused on the history and archives of anthropology, but later opened up to contemporary developments in anthropology and museology. It covered a variety of disciplines and aimed to develop an interaction between text and images. In 2009, the journal was retitled as Anthropology of Art with a new direction.
The Canadian Dental Association publishes JCDA, a peer-reviewed dental journal, every two months. It is commonly known as JCDA.ca due to its transition into a print and electronic knowledge network.

Thatch was a comic strip by Jeff Shesol that began in Brown University's student newspaper and was later syndicated by Creators Syndicate. The strip featured an everyman character who struggled with life and politics, as well as an alter-ego called P.C. Person. Other characters included Thatch's roommate Tripp, editor Kate, and Sloane, described as a "heartless, shallow rich bitch." Shesol ended the strip in 1998 when he accepted a position as speech writer for President Bill Clinton.

The Amoskeag Rugby Football Club, based in Manchester, New Hampshire, competes in Division I of the New England Rugby Football Union. Established in 1984, the club's home field is located at the Northeast Athletic Club in Pembroke, and their team colors are red and black.

The River Forest Public Library is situated in River Forest, Illinois, and is dedicated to providing exceptional service and value to the suburban community of River Forest, which has a population of around 11,000 people. The library is a crucial resource for information, entertainment, and community engagement for individuals of all ages, and it is part of the SWAN consortium, which links libraries in over 80 Chicago suburbs through a shared catalog and other services.

The Prince George Cougars are a Canadian junior ice hockey team in the Western Hockey League's B.C. Division. They play at the CN Centre in Prince George, British Columbia. The team was founded in 1971 as the Victoria Cougars and moved to Prince George in 1994. In 2014, local investors led by Greg Pocock, along with NHL players Dan Hamhuis and Eric Brewer, agreed to purchase the team, which was approved by the WHL Board of Governors.

Kentaro Miura created the characters for the Berserk manga and anime series, which is set in a dark fantasy world inspired by medieval Europe. The story revolves around Guts, a solitary mercenary, and Griffith, the leader of a group of mercenaries known as the Band of the Hawk, who becomes a demon after making a deal with them.

Driewegen is a small town in the Dutch province of Zeeland, previously an independent municipality until 1970. It is now part of the municipality of Borsele and has a population of around 570, with 85 inhabitants in the town itself and a built-up area of 0.017 km² containing 35 residences.

The October Gallery in central London showcases contemporary art from various cultures worldwide and has helped to promote many leading international artists. It is a cultural hub for artists, writers, and intellectuals, hosting talks, performances, and seminars. The gallery's diverse art collection has inspired collectors and enthusiasts, and prestigious institutions worldwide have collected works from the gallery.

Saint Nath Í, also known as Crumnathy, was an Irish saint who founded the monastery of Achonry in the district of Luigne. He was born in Co. Sligo and studied under St Finnián of Clonard. He is remembered as the patron saint of the Irish diocese of Achonry and his festival is celebrated on 9 August.

Marlies Anne van Baalen is a Dutch Dressage equestrian and the daughter of Coby van Baalen. She participated in the 2004 Summer Olympics for the Netherlands and finished 43rd in the individual rankings. She also finished fourth with the Dutch dressage team, which included Anky van Grunsven, Sven Rothenberger, and Imke Bartels.
Aleksandra Trajković, a Serbian pianist born on October 13, 1975, is currently an Assistant Professor and Chief of the Piano Department at the Faculty of Arts in the University of Pristina.

The Cookie Jar Kids Network is a syndicated children's programming block that airs Cookie Jar Group shows on local FOX, MyNetworkTV, and independent stations to meet federal E/I programming requirements. It was formerly known as the DIC Kids Network and was syndicated by Tribune Entertainment from 2003 to 2008, and then by Ascent Media. In 2008, DIC Entertainment was acquired by Cookie Jar Group, and the block was re-launched as the Cookie Jar Kids Network. The block ended on September 18, 2011, and national ad sales were handled by Tribune Entertainment with barter basis available.

The first U.S. Women's Open Golf Championship was held in 1946 at Spokane Country Club in Washington. The 39-player field was reduced to 32 through a 36-hole qualifier, with six professionals and 26 amateurs advancing to match play. The format was 18-hole matches through the quarterfinals and 36 holes for the semifinals and finals. Patty Berg won the championship, beating Betty Jameson 5 and 4 in the final. Berg won $5,600 in war bonds, which was a substantial amount at the time. The tournament format changed to stroke play the following year.
Giulio Coralli, an Italian Baroque painter, was active in Emilia-Romagna and trained under Guercino and Francesco Cairo. He was renowned for his portrait paintings.

St. Finbarr's Hospital in Cork City, Ireland, was originally a Workhouse constructed in 1841. It has since been expanded and renamed several times, and is now responsible for treating medical, surgical, maternity, and infectious cases. It is also the main blood donation center in Cork City.

EduTECH is a yearly conference and exhibition in Australia that focuses on educational technology. It takes place over two days at the Brisbane Convention & Exhibition Centre and brings together primary, secondary, tertiary, and corporate education institutions to explore the potential of technology for teaching and learning.
Stephen Titus Hosmer served as the chief justice of the Connecticut Supreme Court from 1815 to 1833.

The amphibian species Leptobrachium xanthospilum is found only in Vietnam, living in subtropical or tropical moist lowland forests and rivers. Its survival is at risk due to habitat loss. The species is named after its distinctive yellow spots, with the name derived from the Greek words for yellow and spot.
Pat Cronin, an Irish retired hurler, was a right wing-forward for the Clare senior team.

The Mars Volta, a US progressive rock band formed in 2001, released six studio albums, one live album, two extended plays, and nine singles. The band's final lineup included Omar Rodríguez-López, Cedric Bixler-Zavala, Juan Alderete, Marcel Rodriguez-Lopez, and Deantoni Parks. Their first album, De-Loused in the Comatorium, was produced by Rick Rubin and based on the death of artist Julio Venegas. Frances the Mute, their second album, sold over 100,000 copies in its first week and peaked at #4 on the Billboard 200. The band's final album, Noctourniquet, was released in March 2012.

Richard Dorfmeister and Rupert Huber created the electronic music project Tosca in Vienna in 1994. It was Dorfmeister's second project, following Kruder & Dorfmeister. G-Stone Recordings released Tosca's debut album, Opera, in 1997.

Mearns Castle High School is a secondary school located in Newton Mearns, East Renfrewshire, Scotland. It was built in 1978 and serves pupils from several primary schools in the area. The school recently received a new extension through a Public Private Partnership Project with builders HBG. It is located next to Maxwell Mearns Church and Mearns Castle. The school consistently achieves high marks in school performance tables and is ranked 3rd in the most recent Scottish State School of the Year Table (2014).
The Buru thrush is a bird species found only in the montane rainforest of Buru, Indonesia. It was previously considered a subspecies of the Moluccan thrush, which also included the Seram thrush.

Newcastle University Library serves students and staff at Newcastle University, UK, with collections in various subjects. It includes the Philip Robinson Library, Walton Library, Law Library, and Marjorie Robinson Library Rooms. The library has received several awards for excellence and outstanding customer service.
Diminovula aboriginea is a type of sea snail that belongs to the Ovulidae family, which includes false cowries and cowry allies.
The 4th division of men's football in Iceland is known as the deild karla and is the lowest tier in the country's football league system.

Bradford City won the 1910-11 FA Cup, the 40th season of the competition, beating Newcastle United 1-0 in the replay of the final. The trophy design was changed that year, with a new, larger trophy commissioned by Fattorini's of Bradford. The original trophy still exists but is too fragile to be used, so an exact replica has been in use since 1992. The original was sold at Christie's in 2005 to David Gold, who has loaned it to the National Football Museum in Manchester for permanent display.

Rie Tanaka, a retired Japanese artistic gymnast, has two brothers who won silver medals at the London Olympics. She received the Longines Prize of Elegance in 2010 and competed for Japan in the 2012 Summer Olympics, finishing eighth in the Women's artistic team all-around and 16th in the individual all-around.
Xavier Noel, a French welterweight amateur boxer from Guadeloupe, won silver at the 2004 European Championships and competed in the 2004 Summer Olympics.

Monsey Trails is a private bus company that operates on a publicly licensed route in Rockland County, New York. It is owned by a Jewish family of the Skver Hasidic sect and uses a fleet of about 60 coach buses to run 75 scheduled daily commuter trips. The company primarily serves the heavily ultra-Orthodox Jewish west-central portion of the county and offers private bus service between the suburbanized region and New York City. Monsey Tours, a subsidiary, provides charter service. In 1994, the company was involved in a discrimination suit filed by a Jewish woman who was told to leave a men's section. Monsey Trails received mass transit subsidies from New York State amounting to nearly $650,000 in 1993, roughly a quarter of the company's annual revenue. The suit resulted in an out-of-court settlement, in which Monsey Trails agreed not to actively segregate male and female riders for Jewish prayers and to make other accommodations.

Human Events, a conservative American political news and analysis website, announced on February 27, 2013 that it would cease publication of its print edition after 69 years due to financial difficulties, but would continue to maintain its online websites, HumanEvents.com and RedState.com, with original reporting. The magazine had been subsidized by Eagle Publishing, which acquired it in 1993, but the realities of the 24-hour news cycle and the economics of a weekly print publication had become insurmountable. Despite a previous restructuring plan that involved layoffs, the print edition could not continue.
Leicester City F.C. participated in the Football League Championship in the 2006-07 English football season.

The Ultimate Fighting Championship held UFC 18: The Road to the Heavyweight Title on January 8, 1999 in New Orleans, Louisiana. The event was broadcasted live on pay per view in the United States and later made available on home video.

The cult of Our Lady of Begoña commemorates the appearance of the Virgin Mary at the Basilica of Begoña in Bilbao, Spain. She is affectionately known as "Amatxu" and is said to have appeared to locals in the 16th century. The feast day is on 11 October.
Cham Wings Airlines, formerly known as Sham Wing Airlines, is a privately owned Syrian airline based in Damascus.
The Aerodrome, TC LID: CAX5, is situated 3 nautical miles west northwest of Likely, British Columbia, Canada.

Yevgeny Kafelnikov, a former world No. 1 tennis player from Russia, won two Grand Slam singles titles and four Grand Slam doubles titles. He also won the Men's Singles Gold medal at the Sydney Olympic Games in 2000 and helped Russia win the Davis Cup in 2002. Despite having an excellent forehand, backhand, and serve, his lack of regularity caused him to sometimes lose to lower ranked players.

Telfair Museums is the first public art museum in the Southern United States, founded in 1886 through the bequest of Mary Telfair. It houses over 4,500 American and European paintings, sculptures, and works on paper in three buildings: the Telfair Academy, Owens-Thomas House, and Jepson Center for the Arts. Each building represents a different era and houses a collection corresponding to that time period. The Telfair Academy contains nineteenth- and twentieth-century American and European art, while the Owens-Thomas House boasts a decorative arts collection from 1750-1830. The Jepson Center for the Arts features contemporary art galleries and outdoor sculpture terraces.

The BMW S85B50 is a V10 piston engine with DOHC that replaced the S62 and was made from 2005-2010. It was used in the E60 M5 sedan, E61 M5 touring, and E63/64 M6 coupé, and was influenced by BMW's past Formula 1 participation.

The Swan Shopping Centre is an 80,000 square feet shopping centre located in Yardley, Birmingham. It opened in Spring 2012 and is situated on the A45 Coventry Road at the intersection with the A4040 Outer Ring Road, also known as Swan Island.

The ANAVATAN Party, formerly known as ANAP, is a Turkish political party founded in 1983 by Turgut Özal. It merged with the Democratic Party in 2009 but was re-established in 2011 with İbrahim Çelebi as its president. ANAP was a centre-right neoliberal party that supported limited government involvement in the economy, private enterprise, and some public expressions of religion. Özal led the party to victory in the 1983 general election, forming a majority government and briefly restoring democracy.

In their 16th season and sixth in the NFL, the New York Jets aimed to do better than their 7-7 record from the previous year under coach Charley Winner. However, they ended up with a 3-11 record and had the second-highest yards-per-attempt allowed in NFL history for their pass defense.
Dmitry Sholokhov, born in 1980, is a renowned fashion designer who won the tenth season of Project Runway and the fourth season of Project Runway: All Stars.

The Sri Lanka Schools XI cricket team, representing Sri Lankan schools, was formed in 2008 and participated in the 2007-08 and 2008-09 Inter-Provincial Twenty20 tournaments, finishing last both times. Dinesh Chandimal was the team captain.

Romanija is a mountainous region in eastern Bosnia and Herzegovina, located within Republika Srpska and including the towns of Pale, Sokolac, and Han Pijesak. Its highest peak is Veliki Lupoglav and a football club named FK Romanija is based in the nearby town of Pale.

Neptune Township, located in Monmouth County, New Jersey, had a population of 27,935 according to the 2010 US Census, which was a slight increase from the previous two censuses. The township was established in 1879 and named after the Roman water deity due to its location on the Atlantic Ocean. Portions of the township were used to create Neptune City, Bradley Beach, and Ocean Grove.

Järve Centre is a large shopping centre in southern Tallinn, Estonia, with a gross leasable area of 43,000 square metres and nearly 111 shops, including restaurants and cafes. It opened in 2002 and offers a variety of goods and services, including furnishing, leisure and sporting goods, footwear and clothing, and children's goods.

Syntax Records, a San Diego-based American record label, was most active in the late 1990s and 2000s, focusing on alternative hip hop music. Founded by brothers Tim and Steven Trudeau, the label featured a variety of genres and artists, including Ahmad, Tonéx, Braille, LA Symphony, Propaganda, RedCloud, Man of War, Adeem, and Pigeon John. Syntax was named a "Pioneer Classic Record Label" in 2008 by the AEOM Awards. Although Syntax is not currently signing artists or releasing music, its creators founded Syntax Creative, which services record labels and artists with distribution, marketing, and branding. Music is still being released under the Syntax moniker through associated labels such as War Records.
Neasham Belle was a British racehorse who won the Oaks Stakes in 1951 after losing her first two races that year. She had little success as a broodmare.

Nouritza Matossian is a British Cypriot writer, actress, broadcaster, and human rights activist who has written biographies on Greek composer Iannis Xenakis and Armenian painter Arshile Gorky. She also performs a solo show on Gorky's life and contributes to various newspapers and magazines. Matossian was the Honorary Cultural Attache for the Armenian Embassy in London and is fluent in nine languages. She is married to composer Rolf Gehlhaar.
Anghel Nour, a politician from Bessarabia, was the inaugural mayor of Chişinău from 1817 to 1821.

The Skipanon River is a 7-mile tributary of the Columbia River in northwest Oregon that drains an area of coastal bottom land and enters the Columbia from the south at its mouth west of Astoria. It originates from Cullaby Lake in Clatsop County and flows north parallel to the coast, entering the northwest end of Youngs Bay at the mouth of the Columbia. The river's name comes from the Clatsop language and was originally used to refer to a point at the river's mouth.
The Chențu River is a branch of the Drăgan River located in Romania.

Formed in 1987 by the enigmatic "Mr. Doctor," Devil Doll is an experimental rock band from Italy and Slovenia with a devoted following. Their music draws from gothic rock, classical and Slavonic folk music, and features Mr. Doctor's unique sprechgesang style. The band is known for their epic songs, all of which are over 20 minutes long.

Anastasius I the Sinaite was the Greek Patriarch of Antioch twice, but was deposed and exiled due to his opposition to certain imperial doctrines about the Body of Christ. He was later restored to his See with the help of Pope Gregory the Great, but there is confusion about the date of his death and whether there were two bishops with the same name. Some sources claim he was killed by a Jewish mob in 599, while others suggest he died in 598 and was succeeded by another bishop with the same name.

Tamara Nikolayevna Guseva was a Soviet classical pianist and People's Artist of Russia. She graduated from the Moscow Conservatory under Heinrich Neuhaus and won the 9th prize at the IV Fryderyk Chopin competition. She also won the International Youth and Students Festival in Budapest with Yevgeny Malinin. Guseva was a teacher at the Moscow Conservatory and a soloist at the Moscow Philharmonic Orchestra in the 1950s.
Mick Comber played for Melbourne in the VFL and was an Australian rules footballer. He was born on April 17, 1903, and died on January 9, 1975.

Gregory Weldon Meeks is a Democratic U.S. Representative for New York's 5th congressional district, which includes middle and upper middle-class African-American and West Indian American communities, as well as small parts of predominantly middle-class Italian-American communities and Kew Gardens and northern Richmond Hill.

Jörg Kuebart is a retired German Air Force general who served as Inspector of the Air Force from 1991-94. He was born in Allenstein, East Prussia and joined the Bundeswehr in 1956 as a tank commander before switching to the air force in 1957. Kuebart served as a pilot and squadron commander before receiving General Staff Training and commanding the Jagdbombergeschwader 34. He also served as a department director, military attaché, and commander of various divisions before becoming Inspector of the Luftwaffe. After retiring, he served as president of a German veterans organization. Kuebart is married and has three sons.

The Cowichan Valley Regional Transit System provides public bus service in Duncan and the Cowichan Valley of British Columbia, Canada. It has been in service since 1993 and is operated by Greyhound Canada. Additionally, Volunteer Cowichan operates handyDART, a transportation service for people with disabilities who cannot use conventional transit.
Imran Zafar Leghari is a Pakistani politician who became a member of the national assembly in the 2013 general election, representing the Pakistan Peoples Party in NA-233 (Dadu).

Murray Milgate, an Australian economist, is a Fellow and Director of Studies in Economics at Queens' College, University of Cambridge. He co-created and co-edited the original edition of The New Palgrave Dictionary of Economics in 1987 with John Eatwell and Peter Newman.
In 1967, the Pittsburgh Steelers played their 35th season in the NFL.

The Zigana Tunnel is a road tunnel located in northeastern Turkey on the Maçka, Trabzon–Torul, Gümüşhane state highway D-885 E97. It was excavated in two years and is 1,702 m (5,584 ft) long, carrying one lane of traffic in each direction in one tube. The tunnel is situated at Zigana Pass on the Pontic Mountains and has an elevation of 1,820–1,795 m (5,971–5,889 ft) in the north-south direction.
QQ Sweeper is a manga series by Kyousuke Motomi that ended in 2015 and was followed by a sequel called Queen's Quality, both of which are published by Viz Media in North America.

Van der Graaf Generator's live album, Merlin Atmos, was released in February 2015 and features a full performance of their 1971 suite "A Plague of Lighthouse Keepers". The album was recorded during the band's 2013 European tour and a special edition was released with a second CD titled "Bonus Atmos".
Stéphanie Guardia, a former French ice dancer, won the silver medal at the 1995 World Junior and the bronze medal at the 1995 International St. Gervais with Franck Laporte.
The Singapore Handball Association governs the national beach handball team of Singapore, which competes in global tournaments.

The Berkshire Renegades are an American Football team that currently competes in the Premiership South British American Football League.
